<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Devers Advances in Women's Hurdles  </HEADLINE>
By ROB GLOSTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Gail Devers performed as expected in
the women's 100-meter hurdles. Unfortunately for the U.S. men long
jumpers, they also performed pretty much as expected.
</P>
<P>
   Devers, a three-time Olympic gold medalist still seeking the one
medal she has most wanted, got off to a good start by winning her
first-round heat Monday (Sunday night EDT) in 12.62 seconds, the
sixth-best time in the world this year.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Devers in the second round were U.S. teammates Sharon
Couch and Melissa Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   Devers has been one of the world's best hurdlers for the past
decade, but has never won a medal in an Olympic hurdles event. All
three of her gold medals at the Barcelona and Atlanta games --
including two 100-meter titles -- came in sprints.
</P>
<P>
   Also winning a first-round hurdles heat was Gloria Alozie of
Nigeria, whose fiance was killed when he was hit by a car in Sydney
a few days before the games opened. Hyginus Anugo, a 400-meter
runner who had been working out with the Nigerian team, was
crossing a road when he was struck.
</P>
<P>
   In the men's long jump, an event dominated by Americans since
the 1960s, only one of the three U.S. competitors advanced out of
the qualifying round. Dwight Phillips was the lone survivor; Melvin
Lister and Savante Stringfellow were eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   In every Olympics since 1964 -- not counting the Moscow Games
boycotted by the United States -- an American man has won the long
jump. The United States swept the medals in 1988 and 1992, and won
silver and bronze in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But all three Americans were making their Olympic debut in the
qualifying round in Sydney, and that inexperience showed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's unfortunate to see an event where we dominated for so
long come to this,'' said two-time silver medalist and world record
holder Mike Powell, who watched from the stands.
</P>
<P>
   In the first round of the men's 1,500 meters, Hicham El Guerrouj
stuck out his hand and slowed just a bit to allow Spain's Jose
Antonio Redolat to latch on and cross the finish line in tandem.
</P>
<P>
   El Guerrouj, the Moroccan who holds the world record and has not
been beaten in the 1,500 since the end of 1997, edged Redolat by
nine hundredths of a second to win his first-round heat in 3
minutes, 38.57 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   After the race, El Guerrouj said through a translator that he
hurt his leg during the first-round run. Witnesses said his leg was
bleeding after the race, meaning he probably got spiked.
</P>
<P>
   ''It happened 300 meters into the race. It was painful and that
is why I didn't run away from them at the beginning of the race,''
he said. ''It is painful, but I will look after it in the next
couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining El Guerrouj in the semifinals was defending champion
Noureddine Morceli of Algeria, who was second in his heat in
3:38.41. World junior champion William Chirchir of Kenya lost a
shoe during his heat and appeared to be eliminated, but the meet
referee later added him to the semifinals -- saying he was the
victim of interference.
</P>
<P>
   Also advancing were Stanford teammates Michael Stember and Gabe
Jennings, as well as the third American in the race, Jason Pyrah.
</P>
<P>
   In the qualifying round for the women's discus, Seilala Sua of
the United States was among 12 competitors advancing to the final.
Compatriots Suzy Powell and Kristin Kuehl were eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba's Javier Sotomayor, whose drug suspension was reduced in
time for him to compete at the Sydney Olympics, settled for silver
in the high jump Sunday in pouring rain.
</P>
<P>
   The event was won by Sergei Kliugin of Russia, the only
competitor to clear 7 feet, 8&AMP;frac12; inches (2.35 meters). Sotomayor was
second, with a best clearance of 7-7&AMP;frac14; (2.32). Abderrahmane Hammad
of Algeria also cleared 7-7&AMP;frac14;, but took the bronze because he had
one more miss than Sotomayor. The Cuban got his second Olympic
medal -- he was the champion at the 1992 Barcelona Games.
</P>
<P>
   Tereza Marinova of Bulgaria won the women's triple jump with a
leap of 49 feet, 10&AMP;frac12; inches (15.20 meters). Tatiana Lebedeva of
Russia won the silver medal and Olena Hovorova of Ukraine got the
bronze.
</P>
<P>
   In the heptathlon, Denise Lewis of Britain won with 6,584
points. Yelena Prokhorova of Russia won the silver medal with 6,531
and Natalia Sazanovich of Belarus, the 1996 silver medalist, got
bronze this time with 6,527.
</P>
<P>
   Szymon Ziolkowski of Poland won the men's hammer throw at 262
feet, 6 inches. The silver went to Nicola Vizzoni of Italy. Igor
Astapkovich of Belarus won the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Crear, silver medalist at the 1996 Atlanta Games, placed
third in his second-round heat of the men's 110-meter hurdles and
reach the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Freeman ran to victory in her semifinal of the women's 400
meters. Michael Johnson ran cautiously in his semifinal of the
men's 400, but easily qualified for Monday's final.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Alvin Harrison won that semifinal in 44.53 seconds.
Johnson was second in 44.65. The other semifinal was won by another
American, Antonio Pettigrew, in 45.24.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Crear in the semifinals of the 110-meter hurdles was
1996 Olympic champion and U.S. teammate Allen Johnson. Also
advancing were the third American in the event, Terrence Trammell,
and world champion Colin Jackson of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Matete of Zambia, the silver medalist in 1996, had the
fastest time of 48.98 seconds in the first round of the men's
400-meter hurdles. Americans James Carter, Angelo Taylor and Eric
Thomas all also advanced to the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Defending Olympic champion Deon Hemmings of Jamaica won her heat
in the first round of the women's 400-meter hurdles in 55.44
seconds. Also advancing were U.S. hurdlers Kim Batten and Sandra
Glover, but 1996 bronze medalist Tonja Buford-Bailey was
eliminated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
