<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 00:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long Jumpers Make Their Peace  </HEADLINE>
AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- As they passed each other in a hallway
under Olympic Stadium after the long jump, there was a tap on the
shoulder from one, a nod of the head from the other -- an unspoken
acknowledgment between athletes.
</P>
<P>
   With that, Australian long jumper Jai Taurima and American
Savante Stringfellow made their peace Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Taurima finished second in his group with a jump of 8.09 meters,
well behind the 8.32 posted by Ivan Pedroso of Cuba. Stringfellow
was a disappointing ninth in that group with 7.84.
</P>
<P>
   But their jumps took a backseat to the possible tension that
might exist between the two after Taurima's racial remarks before
the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Last month during training in Brisbane, Taurima had called the
American long jumpers ''dribblers'' and said ''you can pretty much
knock out all the dark guys'' because of Sydney's cool conditions.
The American long jumpers were furious at the remarks.
</P>
<P>
   When Stringfellow first came to Sydney, he saw Taurima, shook
hands with him and wished him luck.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Stringfellow was more concerned with his own
disappointing jumps and the medal chances of teammate Dwight
Phillips, who was second in the other long jump group at 8.13
meters, trailing Luis Meliz of Cuba, who did 8.21.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think I did anything right on the runway,'' he said.
''I can't tell you what went wrong. I have to tip my hat to Dwight.
He did a fine job and he has a great chance to medal. He has the
ability and the heart to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then, Australians Peter Burge, who was third behind
Phillips, and Taurima came by. Burge shook Stringfellow's hand. The
American said, ''I'll be here Thursday (for the final).''
</P>
<P>
   Taurima tapped Stringfellow's shoulder as he passed by. There
were no words, just a nod of acknowledgment from the American.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian jumper complained about the cold, damp conditions
and the early start for his event.
</P>
<P>
   ''The weather here -- it changes like bloody Melbourne,'' he
muttered. ''I need a coffee machine in my room.''
</P>
<P>
   When someone asked him about jumping so early, Taurima grimaced.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not a morning person,'' he said. ''I wish the Olympics
were held between 2 and 4 a.m.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 0003 </TRAILER>
