<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 00:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC: Bislett Test Shows Steroid Use  </HEADLINE>
By STEPHEN WILSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- IOC drug chief Prince Alexandre de
Merode said Monday that an athlete tested positive for the steroid
nandrolone at the Bislett Games in late July.
</P>
<P>
   De Merode said the IOC wasn't told the name of the athlete or
the nationality involved. He said the test results have not been
previously disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   IOC vice president Dick Pound said he was told by ''a reliable
source'' that the test involved American shot put world champion
C.J. Hunter, husband of Olympic gold medalist Marion Jones. Hunter
is not competing in Sydney, but is credentialed as a coach for his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   Pound said: ''I haven't seen the results. I don't have any
personal knowledge. But I consider it a reliable source.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he understood that both the IAAF and USA Track &AMP;
Field have been informed.
</P>
<P>
   He further said it ''would be helpful'' if the IAAF, track's
international governing body, and USA Track &AMP; Field would
''indicate what they've done about it.''
</P>
<P>
   A woman who answered the phone at Hunter's hotel room refused to
comment, saying, ''Call his agent.''
</P>
<P>
   A message seeking comment from agent Charles Wells at the same
hotel was not returned.
</P>
<P>
   IAAF general secretary Istvan Gyulai said Monday: ''It would be
premature and irresponsible to comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Masback, head of USA Track &AMP; Field, was unavailable for
comment and messages to his cell phone were not immediately
returned.
</P>
<P>
   De Merode also accused U.S. track and field officials of
covering up five positive drug tests before the 1988 Seoul
Olympics. He said he didn't recall the names of the athletes, but
that some may have won medals during the games.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the positive test from the Bislett Games, de Merode
said the IOC was informed by an Oslo laboratory in early September.
The Bislett Games are a major international track and field
competition.
</P>
<P>
   He said the test showed the presence of nandrolone, a banned
anabolic steroid, at 1,000 times the permitted level. Nandrolone
helps athletes gain strength and muscle bulk by repairing the
damage of high-level training and competition. It has been involved
in hundreds of recent doping cases.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter is not a member of the U.S. Olympic team. He won the U.S.
trials in June but withdrew from the team Sept. 11, eight days
after arthroscopic knee surgery in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney Daily Telegraph, citing unidentified sources,
reported Monday that Hunter had failed a drug test at the Bislett
Games July 28, where he finished second in the shot with a throw of
69 feet, 9 inches. The newspaper said the test showed illegal
levels of both nandrolone and testosterone.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Olympic Committee said it had ''received no
notification of any current or pending positive of any member of
our Olympic team.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules, USA Track &AMP; Field gets any word of drug
positives involving American athletes from the IAAF. It then must
notify the USOC if the athlete is on the Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   ''If any athlete outside the U.S. team would have tested
positive, the national governing body of that sport would have been
notified by now,'' USOC spokesman Mike Moran said. ''To my
knowledge, this has not taken place. The USOC cannot confirm any
positive test of any American athlete, whether a member of the U.S.
team or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones won gold in the 100 meters on Saturday and is trying to
win an unprecedented five gold medals in Sydney. There have been no
reports linking Jones to use of banned performance enhancers.
</P>
<P>
   Gyulai said he was sad that the reports on Hunter were coming
now.
</P>
<P>
   ''I regret that this news is breaking when Marion Jones is
running,'' he said. ''It's terrible whether it's true or not. It
has nothing to do with the Olympics. I personally regret if it's
true or not. If it's not true, it would seem there are efforts to
smear the wonderful days here.''
</P>
<P>
   The 330-pound Hunter had been among the favorites for a shot put
gold medal in Sydney before his injury. Ranked No. 1 in the world
last year after winning the world championship with a throw of
71-6, Hunter also was the bronze medalist at the 1997 world
championships. He is a three-time U.S. champion and the 1995 world
indoor silver medalist. He finished seventh at the 1996 Olympics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 0003 </TRAILER>
