<HEADLINE> Croatia 8, Hungary 7  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- They wear laughable red-checked suits
and feature a scorer named Elvis. But the Croatians marked
themselves as Olympic favorites after an 8-7 victory over Hungary
on Monday that guaranteed them a quarterfinal spot at the Sydney
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis Fatovic, Mile Smodlaka and Samir Barac scored two goals
each to keep Croatia's men's water polo team undefeated and in
first in the Group B standings at 3-0-0.
</P>
<P>
   Hungary, which trailed 8-5 in the fourth quarter, got within a
goal after Tibor Benedek's long shot went past Sinisa Skolnekovic
with 1:12 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Both Benedek and Tamas Molnar had chances to tie in the final
seconds, but could not do it.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first loss at the Olympics for Hungary, 2-1-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Hungarians, who have a record six Olympic golds in the
sport, need one victory in remaining games with the United States
and Yugoslavia to advance.
</P>
<P>
   The Croatians finished with a silver medal in Atlanta and are
looking for more in their second Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Fatovic rallied Croatia from a 4-2 deficit with his two
consecutive scores, both from the left side of the net. Barac put
the Croatians ahead for good when his long shot deflected off two
Hungarian defenders and into the net.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia finishes round-robin play against Yugoslavia and the
Netherlands.
</P>
</TEXT>
