<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, Sept. 25, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Opposition Claiming Yugoslavia Vote
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- After an election Sunday marked by a large
turnout and allegations of fraud, Yugoslavia's once struggling opposition
claimed victory and urged Slobodan Milosevic to peacefully quit power after 13
years of hardline rule. Milosevic, however, showed no signs of conceding defeat.
The state election commission closed up for the night without announcing any
official returns. Voting was plagued Sunday by reports of blatant irregularities
by Milosevic backers, including ballot box stuffing, the few domestic monitors
watching the polls said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Korean Defense Chiefs Meet
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHEJU, South Korea (AP) -- The defense ministers of South and North Korea
held reconciliation talks Monday for the first time in five decades of hostility
across the world's most heavily fortified border. The meeting between South
Korean Defense Minister Cho Sung-tae and Kim Il Chul, minister of the People's
Army of North Korea, marked one of the most significant steps toward
establishing friendly relations on the divided Korean Peninsula since a June
summit of the leaders of both Koreas.ressed in an olive green uniform, Kim
smiled and shook hands with Cho, a former general, at the beginning of their
highly symbolic talks in a five-star hotel. Delegates from both sides included
generals and colonels.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cheney Says Oil Tap Is Political
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton's decision to tap the nation's emergency
oil reserves drew fire Sunday from the GOP vice presidential nominee as a
political move to aid Democrat Al Gore. The action amounted to nothing more than
''tweaking prices six weeks before the election,'' Dick Cheney said, noting that
the vice president proposed the drawdown just before the Clinton
administration's announcement Friday. But Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said
the president was motivated by the potential heating oil shortages this winter
-- not high prices and the political problem they might cause Gore's White House
bid.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Yugoslavia Vote Concerns Clinton Admin.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration, which has made ousting
President Slobodan Milosevic a top priority, said Sunday it was concerned about
fraud and other problems in the bitter election in Yugoslavia. The reported
irregularities come after several months during which the Milosevic regime has
arrested pro-democracy activists and prepared for fraud in both the casting and
the counting of ballots, Boucher said. Sunday's voting was chaotic after
Yugoslavs turned out in large numbers, estimated at higher than 70 percent. The
opposition was claiming victory in an election that could end Milosevic's 13
years in power.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Barak: Partial Agreement Possible
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) --Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said Sunday that he is
prepared for a partial agreement with the Palestinians -- a prospect the
Palestinians said is out of the question. Barak told the Israeli cabinet he does
not rule out the possibility that ''a comprehensive agreement will be achieved
on most of the issues, while a time limit will be set for agreement on a very
small part of them,'' his office said in a news release. In recent days, his
Cabinet ministers have hinted they would accept a deal that delayed decisions on
hot-button issues like Jerusalem.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Motorola, Palm Ally on 'Smart Phone'
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- Motorola Inc. and Palm Inc. are teaming up to
develop a ''smart phone'' for early 2002 release that will serve as a wireless
Internet device, phone and personal organizer. The latest heavyweight alliance
in the race to combine wireless and Web in a single gadget was to be announced
Monday as the top names in technology and electronics gather for the Personal
Communications Industry Association's GlobalXChange conference, this week in
Chicago. Details on the Motorola-Palm device were sketchy, though both companies
envision a color display larger than the screen on current Web-enabled phones,
but smaller than the 3-inch by 4-inch displays featured on today's Palm
organizers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dollar Rises Against Yen
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei gained 304.98 points, or 1.93 percent, to 16,123.23
in early trading. On Friday, the average closed down 492.80 points, or 3.02
percent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
IOC: Hunter Positive For Drug Use
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- American shot put world champion C.J. Hunter,
husband of Olympic gold medalist Marion Jones, tested positive for a banned
substance, international track officials confirmed Monday. Istvan Gyulai,
general secretary of the IAAF, track's world governing body, said the case is
being referred to USA Track &AMP; Field. Hunter is not competing in Sydney, but is
credentialed as a coach for his wife. He won the U.S. trials in June but
withdrew from the team Sept. 11, eight days after arthroscopic knee surgery in
North Carolina. The 330-pound Hunter had been among the favorites for a shot put
gold medal in Sydney before his injury.
</P>
