<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Powell Watches Long Jump in Tears  </HEADLINE>
By ROB GLOSTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Mike Powell sat in the stands, reading
a newspaper and wiping away tears. He tried to watch the long jump,
an event he once dominated, but it was too painful at times.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, a two-time Olympic silver medalist and still the world
record holder, is using the Sydney Games as a catharsis. Attending
the games as an International Olympic Committee guest, he hopes to
finally come to terms with retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was tough for me today. After the first round I just
started crying. I'm not used to sitting and watching the Olympic
long jump,'' he said. ''But I've been waiting for this moment for
the last couple of years. I'm glad I'm here to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching the competition has brought out another emotion in
Powell. Though he knows he's past his prime, Powell watched the
qualifying round Monday (Sunday night EDT) and wondered whether he
had made the right decision to retire.
</P>
<P>
   The futility of the U.S. jumpers, and the overall level of the
Olympic competition, made Powell think ahead to the 2004 Athens
Games.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope they jump better in the final, or I'll think about
getting my creaky old bones out there again,'' he said. ''Who
knows? In 2004 there might be a 40-year-old man out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The best jump in the qualifying round was by Ivan Pedroso of
Cuba, who leaped 27 feet, 3&AMP;frac34; inches (8.32 meters). That's two feet
shorter than the world record of 29-4&AMP;frac12; (8.95) set by Powell in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, who won 34 straight long jump competitions in the early
1990s and won silver at the 1988 and 1992 Olympics, said the poor
overall level of current long jumping led him to contemplate a
comeback this spring -- though he's about 25 pounds heavier than his
usual jumping weight.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was playing pickup basketball in April, dunking over
opponents, when he first thought of returning. He worked out for
three weeks, hoping to get ready for the U.S. trials in July, but
his body wouldn't cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the competition in Sydney is even more painful for
Powell because of the poor performance by the three Americans. Only
Dwight Phillips advanced to Thursday's final, while Savante
Stringfellow and Melvin Lister were ousted in the qualifying round.
</P>
<P>
   The long jump is an event long dominated by American men. In
every Olympics since 1964 -- not counting the Moscow Games boycotted
by the United States -- the winner of the has been an American.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. swept the medals in 1988 and 1992, and won silver and
bronze in 1996. But with no apparent successor to Powell and
four-time Olympic champion Carl Lewis, the years of American
dominance are over.
</P>
<P>
   From Jesse Owens in the 1930s, to Ralph Boston and Bob Beamon in
the 1960s, to Lewis and Powell in the 1990s, Americans have counted
on medals in the long jump.
</P>
<P>
   But all three jumpers this year were making their Olympic debut,
and that lack of experience has hurt. Powell said there was a gap
between his generation and the current group.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that most of the best jumpers we have are younger.
These guys are all college kids. They're supposed to have had
someone to show them the way. But the jumpers that came after me,
they didn't carry the torch,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's unfortunate to see an event where we dominated for so
long come to this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 0109 </TRAILER>
