<DOCNO> APW20000925.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soviet Deserter Faces Deportation  </HEADLINE>
By MATT MOSSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- With the Soviet empire about to collapse, Red
Army soldier Arkady Bykov fled to freedom in the West in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-year-old conscript survived 10 days alone in a German
forest, eating leaves and berries. Then, with fake documents and
helpful friends, he managed to elude authorities for nine years.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Bykov is closer than ever to his greatest fear: going
back to Russia, where military prosecutors have a 1991 warrant for
his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Bykov, now 28, surfaced in Montreal in 1997, believing Canada's
liberal immigration policies would be his best shot to gain asylum.
However, Canada wants to deport him, and he could be sent back to
Russia. His only chance is a plea on humanitarian grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bykov could face 20 years in a Siberian jail if returned to
Russia, according to the Frankfurt-based International Society for
Human Rights. Wanda Wahnsiedler, an advocate there, sent appeals to
immigration officials last week to keep Bykov in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing is scheduled Monday to determine if Bykov, who is in a
detention center, can stay in his Montreal home until his
deportation, his lawyer Nancy Doray said.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials have been trying to deport Bykov since
Aug. 31, a task that hasn't been easy -- mostly because Russian
diplomats in Montreal won't cooperate, saying they only issue the
documents he needs to those who want to go back. And since he never
applied for Russian citizenship after the Soviet Union broke up,
he's officially stateless.
</P>
<P>
   Russian consulate spokesman Michael Gorelov refused to comment
on the case last week.
</P>
<P>
   After fleeing, Bykov said he was rescued from his forest cover
when he asked for help from a family picnicking on the banks of the
Elbe River.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was so dirty, I was afraid they would be scared of me,''
Bykov said. ''But I was weak, I had no power. They gave me
cigarettes. It was the first time I ever smoked.''
</P>
<P>
   They helped him find shelter, and he remained in refugee housing
in Germany for the next six years, Bykov said.
</P>
<P>
   He said fear of deportation and imprisonment finally led him to
sneak back into Russia to buy a U.S. visa. He flew to New York in
February 1997, and decided to seek asylum in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Bykov's lawyer said Friday she will file a plea to keep him in
Canada on humanitarian grounds, which could give him another chance
to tell his story.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they make the application, we would listen to it,'' said
Patrick Defoy, a spokesman for Citizenship and Immigration Canada.
</P>
<P>
   But Doray said the officials she's pleading with aren't so
accommodating. They've heard Bykov's amended version of his
nine-year journey but aren't convinced, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a phone call from jail Friday, Bykov said he has survived
forests and borders and historical tumult, but he's never before
spent a night in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I left military, I thought I would be free,'' Bykov said.
''It's better I die than go to Russia. What's going to happen after
Monday, I don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 0126 </TRAILER>
