<HEADLINE> Greene Picked For U.S. Relay Team  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Maurice Greene, the Olympic 100-meter
champion, and five others were chosen for the 400 relay squad
Monday by track and field coach John Chapman.
</P>
<P>
   Chosen along with Greene were Jon Drummond, Bernard Williams,
Kenny Brokenburr, Brian Lewis and Tim Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of them will run in some combination,'' Chapman said.
</P>
<P>
   The rules permit two changes from round to round in the relay.
The coach said Drummond, Montgomery, Williams and Greene would run
the first round, provided Greene is healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Between the first round, second round, third round and finals,
anything can happen and probably will,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman said Greene complained of being sore after winning the
gold medal, but the coach said that was normal after running two
hard races in the 100.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Greene's leg is sore, that will change something,'' he
said. ''We're not going to do anything stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Drummond was part of the silver medal 400 team at Atlanta in
1996 and ran the lead leg of the gold medal-winning relay team at
the 1999 world championships.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a junior at the University of Florida, is the reigning
NCAA 100 champion. Lewis was fourth and Brokenburr fifth in the 100
at the Olympic trials. Montgomery joined Drummond, Lewis and Greene
on the gold medal 400 relay team at the 1999 world championships.
</P>
</TEXT>
