<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama May Provide Spy Chief Refuge  </HEADLINE>
By KATIA MARTINEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) -- Panama appeared almost certain to bow
to international pressure and grant asylum to disgraced former
Peruvian spy chief Vladimiro Montesinos, adding him to the string
of despised and reviled former leaders spending their sunset years
here.
</P>
<P>
   President Mireya Moscoso is expected to make a final decision
Monday on whether to accept Montesinos, who arrived here on a jet
Sunday and whose supporters had reportedly threatened a coup in
Peru if he wasn't given asylum.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization of American States lobbied for the asylum
Saturday -- apparently in order to help pave the way for a graceful
exit by Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori -- even though some
Panamanians are tiring of their country's role as a Club Med for
aging strongmen.
</P>
<P>
   Some pressure on Panama to reverse its rejection of the asylum
request Saturday may have come from Montesinos and his supporters
in the Peruvian military. Montesinos is viewed as too influential
and dangerous to live in Peru, and, many Panamanians say, too
unsavory to have here.
</P>
<P>
   There was ''a delicate situation in Peru, and if Panama didn't
give asylum, there would have been a coup'' there, said opposition
Panamanian lawmaker Miguel Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The United States supported Panama taking in Montesinos, and
Douglas Barnes, a U.S. embassy spokesman in Lima, talked as though
it was already a done deal.
</P>
<P>
   But some prominent Panamanians opposed giving Montesinos asylum.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once again, Panama is being asked to be the dumping ground for
this type of garbage,'' said former president Guillermo Endara, who
served from 1989 to 1994. Brazil had reportedly turned down a
similar request earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Montesinos, viewed as Fujimori's right-hand man throughout the
1990s, has remained out of sight since mid-September, when Peruvian
broadcasters aired a videotape showing him allegedly bribing the
opposition lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal prompted Fujimori to promise the new elections, in
which he said he would not participate. He also pledged to
dismantle the National Intelligence Service that Montesinos had
headed. The service has been linked to human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Panama has provided asylum for several disgraced Latin American
leaders in recent years. They include former Ecuadorean President
Abdala Bucaram, whose antics during his brief term earned him the
nickname ''El Loco'' or ''The Crazy One.''
</P>
<P>
   Also here is former Haitian dictator Gen. Raul Cedras, who
toppled President Jean Bertrand Aristide in a 1991 coup.
</P>
<P>
   Former Guatemalan president Jorge Serrano Elias, who attempted
to seize absolute power in his country in 1993, is another resident
unlikely to leave: he faces a court judgment at home for illegally
closing a newspaper while in office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 0150 </TRAILER>
