<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman Switches Campaign Trails  </HEADLINE>
By BRIGITTE GREENBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- Joseph Lieberman hopped off one campaign
trail and took a detour onto another, returning to his home state
of Connecticut to campaign for his Senate seat and briefly pushing
aside his campaign for the vice presidency.
</P>
<P>
   State law allows him to compete for both offices at the same
time, though Lieberman's critics -- and even some supporters -- have
questioned the wisdom of doing both.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Lieberman's schedule Monday was a mixed bag -- some
Senate business, some Senate campaigning and a couple of
fund-raisers for the Democratic National Committee, where his role
was that of Al Gore's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Lieberman's vice presidential campaign staff dropped out
of sight for the day so as to avoid any violation of Federal
Election Commission rules, and some old faces from his Senate
office suddenly appeared.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate race, a recent poll shows that Lieberman maintains
a huge lead over his Republican challenger, Waterbury Mayor Philip
Giordano. Lieberman, who is seeking a third term in the Senate, has
a 72-19 percent lead among likely voters, according to a Quinnipiac
University poll released last week.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Lieberman is so popular that his latest job approval
rating --80 percent -- sets a record for elected officials in the
three states where Quinnipiac polls are taken, Connecticut, New
York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   But the poll also found that voters were evenly split, 46
percent no to 45 percent yes, on the question of whether he should
seek re-election at the same he is running for vice president.
Nearly one in four voters said they are less likely to vote for him
for Senate because of his dual candidacies.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano has accused Lieberman of neglecting his job and being
an absentee politician.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman and some other Democrats have said he should stay in
the Senate race, in part because there is not enough time to hold a
primary to find a replacement. Lieberman has said that if he were
to step aside by the Oct. 27 deadline, only a handful of party
leaders would decide who replaces him as the Democratic candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Richard Blumenthal has been widely mentioned as
Lieberman's replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. John G. Rowland has said he would veto any bill
calling for a special Senate election in less than two years,
should Lieberman win both the Senate and vice presidential races.
</P>
<P>
   If Lieberman must resign his Senate seat, Rowland would appoint
his replacement. By law, a special election would be held in 2002
to fill the position, but the state Legislature could call an
election before then.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland has said he would not appoint himself to the seat. He
said a short of list of successors would include Republican Reps.
Christopher Shays and Nancy Johnson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 0204 </TRAILER>
