<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 02:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pagans Find Fellow Believers Online  </HEADLINE>
By RICK CALLAHAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Amid the swirling cigarette smoke in a
downtown coffeehouse, the ancient pantheon of pagan deities comes
alive, conjured up over coffee in the conversation at two adjoining
tables.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana Asatru Council, a group of modern pagans who worship
old Norse deities and a smattering of other gods, has gathered for
its weekly meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Between drags off cigarettes, the talk meanders from Thor -- the
lightning-wielding god of thunder -- to the mysteries of the
universe and then to the Internet, the medium that's helping this
tiny religious community to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Wiccans, Druids, shamans, goddess-worshippers and people who
revere members of the ancient lineup of Roman, Greek, Egyptian and
Celtic deities are showing up online and in public more often these
days. Modeling their emergence after the gay pride movement, many
pagans say they are ''coming out of the broom closet'' -- a wry
reference to the witches among them.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're everywhere. We could be your neighbor or co-worker and
you wouldn't even know it,'' said James McCoy of Kokomo, Ind., a
computer software designer who spends hours online each day with
fellow pagans.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, most pagans preferred to keep their beliefs
secret, fearful of the public's mistaken belief that they are
devil-worshippers. There were no coffeehouse meetings for them.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Brasher, an assistant professor of religion at Mount
Union College in Alliance, Ohio, says the cyber-realm has allowed
isolated believers to connect with like-minded individuals as never
before. It also provides a way to wage an inexpensive public
relations campaign to burnish their beliefs' reputations.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Internet has given these minority religious movements a
public forum to say, 'We don't do evil things, we don't cast spells
and we are environmentally minded,''' Brasher said.
</P>
<P>
   Going online also allows pagans to foster Pagan Pride events,
such as last Friday's autumnal equinox. At such public gatherings,
pagans gather in the full regalia of their particular groups,
frequently eager to engage the general public.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne and Duke Egbert, an Indianapolis couple who serve as
high priestess and high priest of a coven of about three dozen
people, run an Internet site that helps plan pride gatherings
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The Egberts, both 32, started the Web site in 1998 and that year
they organized about 20 pride events. Last year, that rose to about
55; this year about 70 Pagan Pride events are slated in Canada and
36 states.
</P>
<P>
   That includes Pagan Pride Day on Saturday in Indianapolis' Broad
Ripple Park that's expected to attract hundreds. Admission is a can
of nonperishable food that will be donated to a local food pantry.
</P>
<P>
   The Egberts, who have two children, were both raised in
traditional religions, she a Roman Catholic and he an Episcopalian.
</P>
<P>
   By their early 20s both had found Christianity lacking in many
areas, particularly tolerance, as their intrigue grew in pagans'
reverence for nature and emphasis on the free will of the
individual.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most religions will tell you that their beliefs are right and
everyone else is wrong,'' said Duke Egbert, who goes by the pagan
name Dagonet. ''We believe we are right for ourselves. My religious
path is exactly right for me. Other people's religious paths may be
right for them. I can't judge that.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Pagan Education Network: http://www.bloomington.in.us/(tilde)pen
</P>
<P>
   Web Pagans Network: http://web.pagans.net
</P>
<P>
   The Witches Voice: http://www.witchvox.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 0240 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000925.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 02:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Marathon Winner Savors Victory  </HEADLINE>
By ERIC TALMADGE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Like baseball or sumo, the Japanese
love a marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Half or whole or run as a relay, some of the most important
marathons each year are held in Japan. And they are televised,
beginning to end.
</P>
<P>
   The reason?
</P>
<P>
   Several of the world's top marathon runners are Japanese. And
the fastest of them all is Naoko Takahashi, who won gold here
Sunday with what many believe was the best marathon ever run by a
woman.
</P>
<P>
   ''I still can't believe that it's over and I won,'' Takahashi
said Monday after going for her usual morning run. ''I was really
relaxed before the race. I was so relaxed it was actually starting
to worry me a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't hurt her race any, however.
</P>
<P>
   Takahashi, who took the lead and held it for the last four miles
on the hilly course through Sydney, finished with a time of 2
hours, 23 minutes and 14 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   That time was an Olympic best, despite the difficulty of the
course. There are no world or Olympic records in the marathon
because courses differ.
</P>
<P>
   ''I trained harder for this race, and I was feeling good,''
Takahashi said. ''I felt fine until about the 39-kilometer
(20-mile) mark, but then I hit a hill and got really tired.''
</P>
<P>
   The win generated a mini-frenzy in Japan, whose Olympic soccer
team had been eliminated by the United States and whose baseball
team had been narrowly upset by archrival South Korea the night
before.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's state-run television network flashed the news and used
it as the top story most of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Extra editions were issued by newspapers in Takahashi's hometown
in central Japan and in several other cities. In Tokyo, an extra
printed by the Asahi, one of Japan's biggest newspapers, showed her
breaking the tape with the headline ''Takahashi Gold.''
</P>
<P>
   There was even a rumor going around that Takahashi would be
given some sort of a special award upon her return to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But her own celebration was low-key.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ate at McDonald's, and then later had some instant
noodles,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Takahashi's win was certainly a milestone.
</P>
<P>
   Hers was the first gold medal in track ever won by a Japanese
woman. It was also the first marathon gold won by Japan since the
Berlin Games of 1936. But the winner then was not really Japanese --
he was a Korean running for Japan, since Korea was at that time a
Japanese colony.
</P>
<P>
   The results for Takahashi's two teammates were disappointing.
Eri Yamaguchi was seventh, and Ari Ichihashi, who won the silver at
last year's world championships, finished 15th.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has such a depth of talented runners in the marathon that
officials had difficulty choosing the final three. And when they
did, they were soon under fire.
</P>
<P>
   The hubbub -- and it was actually an issue people in Japan cared
about -- was over Harumi Hiroyama being left off the team for Sydney
even though she had a better time than Ichihashi.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese Olympic officials choose Ichihashi because of her world
championships finish. But the selection didn't sit well with many,
especially after Hiroyama beat her at the Osaka marathon in May.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the matter died down. And Hiroyama will still compete
here -- she qualified instead for the 10,000-meter race.
</P>
<P>
   With Takahashi's victory, the next goal will be a world best.
But beyond that, she's too busy savoring the gold to make any
future plans.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I get back to Japan, I want to thank all the people who
have supported me,'' she said. ''And I want to go out and get
something really good to eat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 0241 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000925.0042 </DOCNO>
