<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 02:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Baseball Cheers Dramatic Win  </HEADLINE>
By JOE KAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACKTOWN, Australia (AP) -- Drama seems to find the U.S.
baseball team wherever it goes.
</P>
<P>
   During their preliminaries, the Americans won two games on
dramatic homers -- Mike Neill's two-run shot in the 13th against
Japan, Doug Mientkiewicz's eighth-inning slam against South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Even their informal off-day workout Monday ended with wild
cheering. They cut the workout short, walked next door to the
Olympic softball field and were on their feet when the American
women beat China -- on a 10th-inning homer, of course.
</P>
<P>
   They pointed and shouted congratulations to the U.S. women
celebrating on the field after Stacey Nuveman's game-ending
three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ''Great game!'' manager Tom Lasorda yelled down. ''Great hit!''
</P>
<P>
   Then they headed for their bus, hoping their semifinal game
Tuesday against South Korea doesn't follow the pattern and turn on
the last swing.
</P>
<P>
   Just for once, they'd like to skip the drama. Mobbing
Mientkiewicz after his two-out, full-count slam against the Koreans
in the preliminaries was fun, but fantastic finishes are rare in
medal play.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd like to do it again,'' Mientkiewicz said. ''But hopefully
it would be in the first inning instead of the eighth.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans finished the round-robin tournament tied with Cuba
-- the only team they couldn't beat -- at 6-1. Cuba will play Japan
(4-3) in the other semifinal Tuesday, and the two winners play for
the gold on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   To reach the gold-medal game, the Americans have to beat a team
that played them even until Mientkiewicz's one swing.
Submarine-style pitcher Chong Tae-hyon, the only college player on
Korea's otherwise major league team, gave up only six hits in seven
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Chong releases the ball a few inches above the ground with a
whip motion that had the Americans lunging. Their winning rally
came off the Korean bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hadn't really seen anything like that,'' Neill said. ''It's
tough to recognize what pitch it is because it's coming from an
unfamiliar angle. Hopefully it will help that we've seen some of
his pitches before.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a chance the Koreans' best pitcher could be available.
Chung Ming-tae took a grounder off his shin in the first inning of
a 7-6 win over Japan on Saturday, but X-rays found no fracture.
</P>
<P>
   Teams don't announce their starters before medal-round games, so
the United States was left to guess. In preparation for the
submarine-style starter, coach Reggie Smith threw sidearm as best
he could during batting practice Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As the session wound down on a drizzly, cool day, Lasorda
decided to round up the players and head next door for the softball
field. He led the contingent over dirt paths, walked up a
first-base ramp, raised his arms and yelled to the U.S. dugout:
''We're here!''
</P>
<P>
   Players started the ''USA! USA!'' chant, then went and got some
food and drinks as they settled in and watched the last five
innings. They were on their feet with the rest of the crowd as the
Americans rallied in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda, who autographed a softball and posed for one photo
after another with fans, had promised pitcher Michele Smith that
his team would show up.
</P>
<P>
   ''It meant the world to us,'' she said. ''To hear them up there
cheering for us, that's awesome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 0241 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000925.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 02:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Wrestlers Seek Gold  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN RICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- It was all over for Terry Brands and
Melvin Douglas, former world champions who figured their battered
bodies had spent enough time on the wrestling mat.
</P>
<P>
   Both retired from freestyle wrestling over the past two years.
And then both gave it another shot.
</P>
<P>
   Both now find themselves making a last lunge for Olympic gold
this week in Sydney on a team that is otherwise less experienced
than the U.S. team that dominated the gold medals at the 1996
Atlanta Games.
</P>
<P>
   Brands' twin brother, Tom, won a gold medal in Atlanta, but
Terry -- the 1993 and 1995 world champion -- was upset during
qualifying by Kendall Cross, who went on to win a gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   So Brands charged on, winning the U.S. nationals in 1997 and
1999 in the 127.75-pound (58-kg) class until his body started
sending him emergency messages.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was blacking out in practices and I was getting a
strobe-light effect where it was coming on, going off, coming on,
going off,'' he said during the team's meeting with the press on
Monday (Sunday EDT).
</P>
<P>
   ''Wrestling's great and it's my life but it's still not worth
dying for.''
</P>
<P>
   So the former University of Iowa wrestler, now 32, retired from
competition and took a job as assistant at the University of
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   He also began easing back on a notorious training schedule that
once included 4 a.m. workouts, midday wrestling, evening runs and
nighttime saunas.
</P>
<P>
   Brands said doctors never found a cause for the blackouts, other
than overwork.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really thought in my mind I was done,'' he said. But ''I had
this nagging ambition in the back of my mind and I just started to
wrestle again in practice -- then didn't do anything else, just
wrestled my way into shape over three or four months as opposed to
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of a sudden I was in great shape.... I was doing things
that I was doing before, I just wasn't beating the hell out of my
body.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that with the eased training session, he hasn't suffered
a blackout in a year.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas is the genial, confident old man of the team, a 1993
world champion and U.S. champion in seven of the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel no pressure,'' said Douglas, who is wrestling at 213.75
pounds (97 kg). ''I'm 37. Nobody expects me to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   He retired in 1998. ''I did nothing -- play with my kids and go
to work,'' but did not wrestle. Friends finally persuaded him to
come back and the Home Depot store where he works in Mesa, Ariz,
sponsored him.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why quit if they can't beat me?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I came back, I trained hard, I made the Olympic team,''
Douglas said. ''I feel really feel good about my chances to win the
gold medal.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas said it's sometimes hard to continue. ''Guys I wrestled
with are now coaches. I see those guys go out after a good
training, have a few beers, come home late.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There were a few times when I was coming back that I was ready
to say, 'The heck with it. Why am I doing it?' you know. But I
stuck it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas said younger wrestlers sometimes mistakenly think they
can tire him out, and may be deceived by the fact ''I've got a
little belly on me'' instead of the ''six-pack'' abdomen of the
young weightlifters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told the guys I traded my six-pack in for the keg,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 0242 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000925.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 02:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Wins Parallel Bars Gold  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Li Xioapeng of China won the Olympic
gold medal Monday in the parallel bars with a score of 9.825.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Joo-hyung of South Korea won the silver and Alexei Nemov of
Russia the bronze.
</P>
