<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 02:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colts' Defense Faces Biggest Test  </HEADLINE>
By HANK LOWENKRON
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Indianapolis Colts have had more than
two weeks to prepare for the Jacksonville Jaguars' wide receiving
combo of Jimmy Smith and Keenan McCardell.
</P>
<P>
   They'll show the nation how well they've learned Monday night in
the RCA Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those two guys are outstanding. They had great years last year
and are off to a good start this year,'' Indianapolis coach Jim
Mora said of the duo, who went into this week's action as the AFC's
leaders in receptions and receiving yardage. ''Of our three games
thus far, they're the two best receivers we've faced, definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a Pro Bowl receiver the past three years, has picked up
where he left off last year when he led the league with 116
receptions. He heads into the game with 27 catches for 384 yards
and four touchdowns. McCardell has one less reception, accumulating
284 yards with one touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   And if they're covered, Mark Brunell has been having no trouble
finding tight end Kyle Brady. The Jacksonville tight end has 11
receptions for 124 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no doubt this team gives our defense a good chance to
evaluate itself,'' linebacker Cornelius Bennett said. ''We made too
many mistakes in our last game, and that's why we lost. This is a
Monday night game, one where our peers will be watching and we get
the chance to show our abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis (1-1) and Jacksonville (2-1) have played only once
since the Jaguars joined the league. The Colts won that game in
Jacksonville 41-31 in 1995 -- the Jaguars' inaugural season.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams will be getting back key players who have been
sidelined by injuries since the season began. Jacksonville running
back Fred Taylor returns, while the Colts have wide receiver
Terrence Wilkins and defensive end Mark Thomas back.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has been out since tearing a ligament in his left knee
Aug. 11 in the team's second exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   Colts running back Edgerrin James, a close friend of Taylor, had
some advice for his teammates on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''He can do something of everything,'' James said. ''He can make
some big plays. He can take it the distance in a heartbeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Taylor, the Jaguars have had little success running.
They're 26th among the league's 31 teams, averaging 83 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once we get 28 (Taylor) back, the running game will be fine,''
Brunell said.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts are coming off their bye week following a 38-31 loss
to Oakland in a game Indianapolis led 24-7 at halftime.
Jacksonville rebounded from a 39-36 loss to Baltimore by defeating
Cincinnati 13-0 -- the franchise's first shutout ever.
</P>
<P>
   McCardell had Jacksonville's only touchdown on a 21-yard pass
from Brunell.
</P>
<P>
   McCardell and Jacksonville coach Tom Coughlin are hoping for
more consistency from the team.
</P>
<P>
   ''One week the offense is good, one week the defense is good,''
Coughlin said. ''It's always been a problem here. I hope it isn't
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis is making its first appearance on Monday Night
Football in nearly three years.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts will be looking for a significant improvement in the
takeaway-giveaway department. Indianapolis has only one takeaway in
its first two games and has five turnovers with three interceptions
and two lost fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville may face the no-huddle offense during the game --
the Colts used it effectively in building its lead against Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're always capable of doing it. Some weeks we will have it
more into our plan than other weeks. But, every team we play has to
prepare for it,'' Mora said. ''One of the advantages is if you get
a certain personnel group on the field, and they have a certain
personnel group on the field, it's hard for them to substitute when
you do the no-huddle. So you might get them at a disadvantage. It
just kind of breaks their rhythm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 0249 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
