<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 02:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Who Needs Keyshawn Or The Tuna?  </HEADLINE>
By DAVE GOLDBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who's the flashlight now, Keyshawn?
</P>
<P>
   And, by the way, if Bill Parcells is a genius, what's Al Groh?
</P>
<P>
   Those two questions were among the major items that emerged from
the NFL season's most overhyped game, the ''Keyshawn Bowl'' pitting
Groh's New York Jets against Keyshawn Johnson's new team, the Tampa
Bay Buccaneers.
</P>
<P>
   It's not so much that the Jets won to go 4-0 and leave the Bucs
at 3-1. It's the way it happened -- with two TDs in the final two
minutes after Tampa Bay had what, with its defense, carried what
looked like an insurmountable 17-6 lead through most of the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   It's not even that Chrebet, ridiculed all week by Johnson as ''a
flashlight to my star,'' caught an 18-yard TD pass from running
back Curtis Martin for the winning score. Or that Johnson had
exactly one catch for 1 yard. Or that Groh had the guts to approve
the halfback option call by offensive coordinator Dan Henning.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting factor was how Groh changed the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point came early in the fourth quarter when Groh
pulled the ineffective Vinny Testaverde for one series and inserted
Ray Lucas, the backup who played so well in Testaverde's absence
last season and during the exhibition season.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets went three and out with Lucas at quarterback.
Meanwhile, Groh and linebacker Bryan Cox were encouraging
Testaverde on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   On the next series, Testaverde was back in, leading the Jets on
an 80-yard drive that brought New York to 17-14, with the 2-point
conversion. When Mike Alstott lost a fumble on Tampa Bay's next
possession, the outcome suddenly seemed inevitable the other way --
and it was.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we go down. We go down with our leaders,'' said Cox, who
was run off the Bears for his temper but is one of the most
respected locker room leaders in the NFL. ''Ray's a great
quarterback, but I told Vinny we live and die with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Give that credit to Groh, who apprenticed under Parcells as an
assistant with the Giants, Patriots and Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was a Parcells-like tactic -- the Tuna's forte is playing
with the mind of his players and pushing all the right buttons. But
how many rookie coaches would play with the mind of a veteran
quarterback in a return to the city where he played the first eight
seasons of his career?
</P>
<P>
   Still, a lot of that gets lost in the sideshow.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson spent the week going after Groh, whom he apparently
blames for the trade and Chrebet, whom he has ridiculed since he
joined the Jets, including in his book, ''Throw Me the Damn Ball,''
written after his rookie season with a 1-15 team.
</P>
<P>
   This week, it was the ''flashlight'' remark.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very happy for Wayne,'' Groh said after the game. ''The
power of 46 flashlights made it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   TO CHALLENGE OR NOT TO CHALLENGE: Tony Dungy was 0-for-1999
when instant replay returned. Whatever he challenged was upheld. If
someone challenged a play made by his Bucs, it also went against
him.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe he was gun shy Sunday when he didn't challenge a call
in which Jacquez Green was ruled out on the 11 when it appeared he
either got in for a score or went out at the 1. The Bucs had to
settle for a field goal and Tampa Bay lost by four.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing happened in Chicago, when James Stewart scored
what turned out to be the winning touchdown for Detroit. The ball
never appeared to cross the goal line, but coach Dick Jauron never
challenged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 0250 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000925.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 02:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Youngest Water Polo Member Shines  </HEADLINE>
By PETE IACOBELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Only once during the Olympics has Tony
Azevedo felt like a kid. And it wasn't in the pool.
</P>
<P>
   ''The opening ceremonies, I was like 'Wow,''' said Azevedo, at
18 the youngest member to ever play on the U.S. men's water polo
team. ''I'm here talking to Marion Jones and Lindsay Davenport is
sitting next to me. It was kind of shock.''
</P>
<P>
   In the week leading up to America's first game, Azevedo regained
his focus without losing his teen-age style.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not here to meet all these people,'' he says. ''We're
here to rock and roll.''
</P>
<P>
   Azevedo and 30-year-old teammate Chris Humbert finally got
things rolling for the United States, who won for the first time,
12-8, over the Netherlands at the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   Humbert, one of the world's best scorers, had four goals.
Azevedo had three, all from the outside, to keep America alive for
the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   Azevedo's last score, a bolt of lightning past Dutch goalie Arie
van de Bunt, put America ahead 7-4. The Netherlands never seriously
threatened after that.
</P>
<P>
   How can U.S. coach John Vargas put so much faith in someone who
says his best achievement was being named MVP of his high school
league?
</P>
<P>
   Easy, Vargas says, because Azevedo was born to play water polo.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody would think he's this young kid. He's so intelligent,''
Vargas said. ''He just seems to be a step ahead of everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll have to be if the United States hopes to move on. The
Americans meet Hungary, a gold-medal favorite, Tuesday and then
take on an improving Greek team in their last round-robin match.
</P>
<P>
   Azevedo says the United States needs a second win to be among
the four teams from the their group in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Azevedo special, his teammates say, is how he blends
in with the older players. ''He belongs here,'' said U.S. goalie
Dan Hackett, 29.
</P>
<P>
   Azevedo got to show off his style against the Netherlands. He
can rifle balls through very small openings, as he did when he fit
a goal into about two feet of space between van de Bunt and net's
top left corner.
</P>
<P>
   But Azevedo will happily feed his two-meter scorers, like when
he got the ball to an open Humbert for an American goal.
</P>
<P>
   Azevedo grew up with a passion for water polo and worshipped
Spain's great Manuel Estiarte, playing his sixth Olympics. When
Azevedo faced Estiarte for the first time last summer, the prep
star was awed. ''I was like, 'Oh my God, I can't believe I'm doing
this,''' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Azevedo and Estiarte share similar builds and games. Azevedo is
6-foot-1, only three inches taller than Estiarte in a sport
dominated by 6-7 stars like Humbert.
</P>
<P>
   That's where smarts come in, said Vargas, the U.S. coach, and
that's where Azevedo excels.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's unique,'' the coach said. ''You're not going to see too
many like him come around.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Azevedo had trouble finding his spot on the national
team. He was afraid to shoot and always ready to defer to the older
guys. But team captain Chris Oeding encouraged him to get
aggressive, keep shooting, play his game.
</P>
<P>
   ''That helped me,'' Azevedo said.
</P>
<P>
   He has continued that so far at the Olympics. He has five goals,
tied with veteran Wolf Wigo for second among the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Azevedo still likes the U.S. chances at Sydney. ''We always play
better toward the end of tournaments,'' he said. ''We can only go
up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 0252 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
