<DOCNO> APW20000925.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 02:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Action Shifts Back To The Water  </HEADLINE>
By JOCELYN NOVECK
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- With track taking a rest day and
gymnastics and swimming over, what's an Olympics junkie to do?
</P>
<P>
   No worries, as the Aussie hosts would say.
</P>
<P>
   A dynamic diver from Puerto Rico, Mark Ruiz, is keeping U.S.
momentum alive and evoking comparisons to Greg Louganis as he goes
for gold in Tuesday's springboard competition.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz's quest, to be featured by NBC in prime time, comes just
two days after American Laura Wilkinson stunned the defending
champion Chinese on the 10-meter platform, winning the first gold
for U.S. women in 36 years.
</P>
<P>
   And Ruiz won't be alone: Also advancing Monday in the 3-meter
springboard was teammate Troy Dumais, who was admitted to a
hospital for kidney stones during the U.S. Olympic trials and came
back just in time to qualify for the team.
</P>
<P>
   It was a satisfying day for Ruiz, America's best hope in diving
coming into the Olympics. He disappointed fans earlier in the week
when he and teammate David Pichler placed seventh out of eight
teams in the 10-meter synchronized dive.
</P>
<P>
   The powerhouse Chinese won three of four diving golds in Atlanta
four years ago, but they are still seeking their first victory of
these games.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't want to do anything great,'' Ruiz, who prefers
platform events, said of his qualifying dives, which left him in
fourth place after nearly four hours of competition. ''I didn't
want to hit the board or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the finals, he said, ''I'm not going to hold anything
back.'' The semifinals and finals will both be held Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz taught himself to dive by jumping off tree branches in his
hometown of Toa Alta, Puerto Rico, and by sneaking with his mother
into hotel pools. She thought he might be a budding swimmer, but he
didn't like to swim; he just liked to dive in.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 13, his mother moved with him to Orlando, Fla., so
he could pursue his training. She held down two jobs to make ends
meet.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz could have competed for Puerto Rico, but decided it would
be much more beneficial to immerse himself in the deeper U.S.
talent pool. ''I know I'm Puerto Rican. I take a lot of pride in
that also,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He's always idolized Louganis; when he was young, he took ballet
lessons because his coach told him Louganis had.
</P>
<P>
   But Ruiz deflects the comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will never be another Greg Louganis, just like they'll
never be another Michael Jordan,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The diving comes on a relatively slow day at the Olympics, with
a day off for track athletes. Prime-time coverage includes women's
cycling, sychronized swimming and a gymnastics retrospective
performance. During the day, NBC will show the gold-medal game in
women's softball.
</P>
<P>
   On cable, CNBC will show boxing, soccer and wrestling, and MSNBC
has baseball, tennis and more soccer.
</P>
<P>
   History buffs note: Viewers will be able to catch a water polo
game featuring the Hungarian team that evokes chilling memories
from nearly a half-century ago. The Hungarians play the United
States, part of NBC's late-night coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Nationalism often has played a role in the Olympics. But the
Hungary-Russia water polo match at the Melbourne Games in 1956,
remembered by some as the ''Blood in the Water'' contest, took
things to another level.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks earlier, Soviet troops had invaded Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was no love lost between the countries,'' says former
Hungarian player Ervin Zador, now living in Stockton, Calif. ''We
got out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Zador, then 20, says that for his teammates, shattered by what
was happening in their country, the game with Russia was the only
way they could fight back.
</P>
<P>
   But he said Hungary was also keen for the gold medal -- it had
won four of the previous five -- and knew how to frustrate the
Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't expect it to get out of hand, but that suited us,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   With Hungary ahead 4-0 and a minute left, Russian captain
Valentin Prokopov hit Zador. The wound took 13 stitches to close.
</P>
<P>
   Hungary's fans booed, and moved from their seats to railings
around the pool. Officials stopped the game, and police escorted
the Russians out of the aquatic center. Hungary went on to win the
gold in the next game.
</P>
<P>
   About half of Hungary's Olympic team, Zador said, did not return
home after the Melbourne Games. He was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   He's coached water polo in West Coast clubs and high schools,
and his daughter, a water polo player at USC, barely missed a spot
on this year's Olympic women's team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 0253 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000925.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 02:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Titans 23, Steelers 20  </HEADLINE>
By TOM WITHERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Steve McNair's bruised sternum kept him from
getting the start. His heart carried him to the finish.
</P>
<P>
   McNair came off the bench to replace a dizzied Neil O'Donnell in
the final minutes Sunday and drove Tennessee to the game-winning
touchdown on just four plays, leading the Titans to a 23-20 win
over the Pittsburgh Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   McNair's 18-yard TD pass to Erron Kinney with 1:25 remaining
rallied the Titans (2-1) to their sixth straight win over the
Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's not another quarterback in the league who could do
that,'' Titans left tackle Brad Hopkins said. ''He comes in cold
with a bruised sternum and leads us like that. That's what we
expect.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair had limited practice time all week and didn't start
because of the injury suffered while taking a hit in a Sept. 10
victory over Kansas City. He was relegated to backup duty behind
Neil O'Donnell, and was only going to be used in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   One arose late in the fourth when O'Donnell, making his first
start at Three Rivers Stadium since 1995, was wobbled and bloodied
by a sack by Steelers linebacker Jason Gildon.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie George took one look at O'Donnell and called timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ''He couldn't stay in the game,'' said George, who scored on a
20-yard run in the first half. ''I looked in his eyes and he was
gone. I didn't want their defense getting all pumped up, so I
helped him off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   After one of Tennessee's equipment managers scrambled to get his
helmet, McNair took just a few warmup tosses and entered with the
Titans down 20-16 and facing a third-and-11.
</P>
<P>
   But from his own 36, McNair, whose only significant practice
this week came running the two-minute drill, completed a 22-yard
pass to Chris Sanders on his first attempt, and then ran for 9 more
yards, taking a shot as he hit the turf.
</P>
<P>
   McNair then hit Derek Mason for 15 yards to the 18 before
finding Kinney wide open on a blown coverage for the go-ahead TD.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew from the coverage they were playing, Erron was going to
be against a linebacker and I'll take Erron against a linebacker
every day,'' McNair said. ''I saw he was so open. I just didn't
want to overthrow him.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair's magic act was nothing new to the Titans. He had similar
days last season in leading Tennessee to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ''Steve's a hero,'' George said. ''He's done this numerous
times. When our backs are to the wall, he comes out and makes
plays. That's why he's Steve McNair.''
</P>
<P>
   In five plays, McNair went 3-for-3 for 51 yards, ran for 9 more
and then took a knee to run out the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ''He had that look in his eye, and once he found his helmet, he
got in there and made some plays,'' Titans coach Jeff Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   McNair's heroics were nearly matched by Kordell Stewart, who
nearly brought the Steelers (0-3) back.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who earlier scored on a 1-yard plunge, was forced in
when starter Kent Graham injured his right hip with 1:10 remaining
when he was drilled by Kenny Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart moved the Steelers to the Titans 32, but for the second
straight week, Pittsburgh didn't convert a last-second field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Kris Brown's 50-yard field-goal attempt with 18 seconds
remaining was short, and the Steelers lost by the same 23-20 score
they did a week ago at Cleveland when they failed to get the
field-goal unit in the game in time.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's two weeks in a row that it's heartbreaking,'' Graham
said.
</P>
<P>
   Al Del Greco kicked three field goals for the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, which lost wide receiver Kevin Dyson last week for
the season, came away hurting.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive lineman Joe Salave'a was taken to the hospital as a
precautionary measure after injuring his neck in the first half.
Tight end Frank Wycheck suffered a concussion while making a catch
and didn't return, and Jevon Kearse has a hip flexor.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Scott had two interceptions for Pittsburgh, which has lost
10 of 11 and is 0-3 for the first time since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ''We gave up too many big plays,'' Scott said. ''We can't be
giving up 300-yard passing games.''
</P>
<P>
   DeWayne Washington's interception -- Pittsburgh's third off
O'Donnell -- helped set up the Steelers' go-ahead score, a 5-yard
run by Jerome Bettis that made it 20-16 with 7:50 to play.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Bettis gained 77 yards and moved past Hall of Famer Jim
Taylor into 15th place on the career rushing list. ... Tennessee
improved to 17-2 vs. the AFC Central since 1998. ... Kearse's NFL
record of getting at least one-half sack ended at 13 games. ...
Carl Pickens had his first 100-yard receiving game with the Titans,
and the 20th of his career.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 0253 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
