<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Arrested for Indonesia Bombings  </HEADLINE>
By DANIEL COONEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Police investigating a series of
bombings that have terrorized Jakarta arrested two members of the
armed forces after a shootout, officers said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Police Gen. Bimantoro said the two had acted as individuals and
denied suggestions the military as a whole was behind the deadly
blasts, which included an explosion at the Jakarta Stock Exchange
on Sept. 13 that killed 15 people. Twenty-seven people were
arrested over the weekend in connection with the blasts.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. John Bahril, a police chief in the city of Bandung
where the two military members were arrested, said one of them shot
at police, injuring two officers. Police returned fire, injuring
the gunman, before arresting both suspects, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Local television said the two were members of the army's
Kopassus special forces, which specializes in counterterrorist
tactics and has been accused of human rights abuses. Police said
they could not confirm the two were members of the special force.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the blasts had coincided with advances in a corruption
case against former dictator Suharto, and many have speculated they
were the work of his supporters and elements of the security forces
opposed to President Abdurrahman Wahid's democratic reforms.
Lawyers for Suharto, who was ousted from office in 1998 amid
pro-democracy protests, have denied that.
</P>
<P>
   One of the 27 suspects arrested told police the group had also
planned to attack the U.S. Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives have said most of the detainees, including the two
military personnel, were from the northwestern province of Aceh.
</P>
<P>
   The province has been wracked by years of separatist violence.
In the provincial capital, Banda Aceh, police defused a homemade
bomb Monday that had been planted at a government tax office,
security forces said.
</P>
<P>
   Acehnese rebels have denied any involvement in the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid installed Bimantoro as the national police chief Saturday
and ordered him to take quick action to stop the attacks, which the
president claimed were designed to undermine his reformist
11-month-old government.
</P>
<P>
   Parliamentary Speaker Akbar Tandjung said Monday that lawmakers
want Wahid to justify his firing of the former police chief without
its approval. Akbar said Wahid failed to follow existing
regulations and Parliament would summon him to appear before it
after the president returned from a foreign tour.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid has said he made the change after police disobeyed his
order to arrest Suharto's youngest son, Tommy, in connection with
the bombing of the stock exchange. Police questioned Tommy but
released him two hours later, saying there was insufficient
evidence to hold him.
</P>
<P>
   Bimantoro said Monday that Suharto's family has handed over more
than 100 firearms to police on Wahid's orders. The guns were for
hunting or were collector's items, he said, but did not mention
whether Suharto's private bodyguards had turned in their
military-style weapons in line with Wahid's demand.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests coincided with peace talks in Switzerland between
Indonesian government negotiators and rebel representatives, both
of whom agreed to extend a cease-fire in Aceh.
</P>
<P>
   The separatist Free Aceh Movement has been fighting Indonesian
rule for more than 25 years. More than 5,500 people have died in
the conflict.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
