<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Vows Force vs. Militias  </HEADLINE>
By IRWAN FIRDAUS
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATAMBUA, Indonesia (AP) -- Militias stopped surrendering weapons
to police in West Timor on Monday, and Indonesia's government
pledged to disarm the groups forcibly within three days.
</P>
<P>
   Police in the town of Atambua, where three foreign aid workers
were slaughtered by a militia mob earlier this month, said no arms
had been handed in Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, several militias gave up hundreds of weapons, mainly
homemade guns, in line with government demands aimed at satisfying
international calls for the militias to be controlled.
</P>
<P>
   But that stopped Sunday, when militia members and security
forces clashed after a visit to Atambua by Vice President Megawati
Sukarnoputri. The groups attacked police, grabbed automatic rifles
they had earlier surrendered and threatened to shoot officers.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of angry militiamen demanded their weapons be returned.
Police refused.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of us have fled into the hills with our guns,'' one
militia member said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The militias are the same groups that devastated neighboring
East Timor after the territory voted in a U.N.-organized ballot
last year to end Indonesian rule. Critics claim they are intent on
destabilizing East Timor's transition to self-rule and preventing
120,000 East Timorese refugees in West Timor from returning home.
</P>
<P>
   The latest clash occurred near the U.N. office in Atambua where
three aid workers were killed Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's top security minister, Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono,
said the militias have three more days to hand in their weapons or
their guns will be taken from them by force.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday, the militias had surrendered 34 automatic rifles,
nine grenade launchers, about 1,000 homemade weapons and about
1,000 rounds of ammunition. But Yudhoyono said the groups had yet
to surrender at least 100 automatic rifles.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government has given a three-day deadline for the militias
to surrender their weapons to police,'' he said. ''After that we
will force them to give up their arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Defense Secretary William Cohen warned that Indonesia
risked losing international financial assistance if it fails to
immediately disband the armed gangs.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's Foreign Minister Alwi Shihab is scheduled to brief
the Security Council on Oct. 12 about progress made in West Timor,
the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   But the territory's U.N. administrator, Sergio Vieira de Mello,
said he was skeptical of Indonesia's disarmament program.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do not believe that the militias will voluntarily surrender
their weapons and if they do, they probably will surrender the old
rotten ones and keep the modern ones,'' he said in East Timor's
capital, Dili.
</P>
<P>
   East Timorese independence leader Jose Alexandre ''Xanana''
Gusmao said Sunday's violence ''was a show of the incapability and
incapacity of Indonesia's military members to control the
militias.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
