<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 12.95; Nasdaq Adds 43  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose Monday morning, extending Friday
afternoon's rebound from a market-jolting profit warning by Intel.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-morning trading, the Nasdaq composite index was up 43.91
at 3,8470.67, more than erasing all remaining damage from Friday
morning's technology selloff.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 12.95 at 10,860.32 after
giving back most of an early 50-point gain, while the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index was up 2.58 at 1,451.30 and the Russell 2000
index of smaller companies was up 1.57 at 520.39.
</P>
<P>
   Intel was up $1.156 per share at $49.094 as the most active
Nasdaq issue and one of the Dow's biggest gainers.
</P>
<P>
   The strong open came as world finance officials, facing the twin
threats of soaring oil prices and a weak European currency,
gathered in Prague for the annual meetings of the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank. The finance ministers spent the
weekend putting together joint statements intended to show their
resolve to deal with the two problems, which are threatening
current global prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   When markets opened Monday, they saw initial success on both
fronts. The euro, used by 11 European Union nations, held firm with
where it finished Friday after finance officials staged a surprise
joint intervention in currency markets to boost the euro. Oil was
down by $1.20 per barrel on the London futures market, with Brent
crude from the North Sea trading at $30.05 on contracts for
November delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 ratio on the
Nasdaq Stock Market, but held only a narrow lead on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume came to 131.59 million shares, down from 176.12 at
the same point on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1.1 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 1.2 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 1.3 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
