<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Parties Begin Peace Talks  </HEADLINE>
By SUKHDEV CHHATBAR
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARUSHA, Tanzania (AP) -- Burundian political parties and interest
groups began talks Monday to select the leader of a transitional
government and begin implementing a power-sharing agreement aimed
at ending the country's seven-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations were the first between representatives of 10
Tutsi parties, seven Hutu political groups, the government and the
army since each signed an accord brokered by former South African
President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   Burundian President Pierre Boyoya, the heads of three hard-line
Tutsi parties and representatives of the two main Hutu rebel groups
gathered in Nairobi, Kenya last week. But they failed to agree on a
cease-fire, and rebel attacks -- particularly around the capital,
Bujumbura -- have been on the increase.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bomani, the head of Mandela's mediating team, said the
weeklong talks in Arusha would concentrate on the selection of the
transitional leader and the nomination of eight members of a
committee that would oversee the implementation of the peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the 19 groups also will begin the process of nominating
three representatives each to the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The power-sharing agreement calls for national institutions,
including the army, to be proportionally balanced between majority
Hutus and minority Tutsis. The transitional government would last
three years and lead to democratic elections.
</P>
<P>
   At the opening of Monday's talks, Bomani called the signing of
the accord a ''major achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It takes quite a bit of time to get all parties to sign a
peace accord, but within a very short period of three weeks all
parties have accepted the peace agreement,'' he said. ''The
document signed is not a Bible or a Quran. It can be modified or
amended procedurally.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Aug. 28 signing ceremony in Arusha -- attended by
African leaders and President Clinton -- Mandela's efforts have been
hampered by the rebels' refusal to sign a cease-fire until what
they term political prisoners are released.
</P>
<P>
   Regional leaders at the Nairobi summit gave the government and
rebels 30 days to sign the cease-fire or face international action,
although it was not clear what form that would take.
</P>
<P>
   Bomani said Monday the escalation of the violence was hampering
implementation of the accord and had to be dealt with immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Burundi's civil war began in 1993 when paratroopers from the
Tutsi-dominated army assassinated the country's first
democratically elected president, a Hutu. More than 200,000 people,
mostly civilians, have been killed since then in attacks by the
army and the rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 1131 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000925.0074 </DOCNO>
