<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Gains 47; Dow Adds 8  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher Monday, with
technology shares extending Friday afternoon's rebound from a
market-jolting profit warning by Intel.
</P>
<P>
   In late morning trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite
index was up 47.34 at 3,851.10, erasing all remaining damage from
Friday morning's technology selloff.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 7.77 at 10,855.14 after
giving back most of an early 50-point gain, while the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index was up 4.25 at 1,452.97 and the Russell 2000
index of smaller companies was up 2.00 at 520.82.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems was up $4.13 a share at $122.13 to lead the
Nasdaq advance, while IBM was up $1.56 at $125.56 as one of the
Dow's biggest gainers.
</P>
<P>
   Among the day's big movers, Ciena rose $13.33 to $134.08 after
the maker of optical network equipment announced a major order from
Korea Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   The market's advance came as world finance officials, facing the
twin threats of soaring oil prices and a weak European currency,
gathered in Prague for the annual meetings of the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank. The finance ministers spent the
weekend putting together joint statements intended to show their
resolve to deal with the two problems, which are threatening
current global prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   When markets opened Monday, they saw initial success on both
fronts. Oil was down on the futures market, while the euro, used by
11 European Union nations, held firm with where it finished Friday
after finance officials staged a surprise joint intervention in
currency markets to boost the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 ratio on the
Nasdaq Stock Market, but held only a narrow lead on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume came to 306.68 million shares, down from 414.72
million at the same point on Friday.
</P>
