<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maoist Rebel Attack Leaves 12 Dead  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) -- Maoist rebels hurled crude bombs and
fired guns at a police station in a mountain town in Nepal on
Monday, killing at least 12 officers and seriously injuring 36,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the rebels also bombed the district administration
office and attacked the jail, freeing dozens of their friends. The
attack -- which began at about 12:45 a.m. -- was the first major
assault on a district headquarters in Nepal and the first near Lake
Phuksundo, a popular trekking area for Western tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers from a camp two miles away were unable to help, as the
rebels mined the path from the army camp to the town, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven of those killed in Dunai, headquarters of Dolpa district
200 miles northwest of the capital, Katmandu, were burned beyond
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue helicopters flew 24 of the injured to Katmandu, while the
rest were taken to hospitals at Nepalgunj, the largest town near
Dunai.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Maoist rebels began a guerrilla insurgency more than
four years ago in the mountains of Nepal, the rebels have killed at
least 209 police and lost 979 of their own fighters and supporters,
the government says. At total of 249 civilians have been either
killed by the rebels or caught in the cross fire between the
guerrillas and the police.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are demanding an end to Nepal's constitutional
monarchy and the feudal structure in parts of the country. They
also allege police repression.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
