<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North Korea Reports Crop Damage  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- North Korea said Monday that the
hunger-stricken communist state has lost over 1.4 million tons of
grain this year because of drought, heat waves and tropical storms.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is certain that the shortage of food will continue next
year, too,'' North Korea's official foreign news outlet, KCNA,
quoted a government statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. World Food Program launched another appeal for food aid
for North Korea this month, saying nearly 8 million of North
Korea's 22-million population would be short of food unless donors
come up with $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea said much of its farmland received little rain
during the sowing season of rice and maize, two main crops in North
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Reservoirs and paddy fields dried up, and crops withered during
the drought and heat waves that continued until mid-August, said
the statement.
</P>
<P>
   The drought and heat cost North Korea more than 360,000 tons of
rice and 660,000 tons of maize, it said.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea is now in its sixth consecutive year of food
shortages. Its agriculture-based economy has been suffering since
the collapse of the Soviet Union. The communist regime started
asking for food aid in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea asked South Korea for one million tons of grain in
food loans during high-level talks in August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
