<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Up 15; Dow Gains 6  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned mixed Monday after an early
followthrough to Friday's rebound from a market-jolting profit
warning by Intel.
</P>
<P>
   At midday on Wall Street, the technology-led Nasdaq composite
index was up 15.36 at 3,819.12 after gaining nearly 65 points in
early trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up just 5.92 at 10,853.29
after giving back most of an early 50-point gain, while the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index was up 0.88 at 1,449.60 and the
Russell 2000 index of smaller companies was up 1.04 at 519.86.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems was up $4.48 a share at $122.48 to lead the
Nasdaq advance, while IBM was up $1.13 at $125.13 as one of the
Dow's stronger components along with American Express, up $1.50 at
$60.25, and United Technologies, up $1.50 at $67.
</P>
<P>
   Among the day's big movers, Ciena rose $13.38 to $134.13 after
the maker of optical network equipment announced a major order from
Korea Telecom. Sprint PCS rose $3.38 to $31.38 after Lehman
Brothers upgraded the mobile phone company.
</P>
<P>
   The market's advance came as world finance officials, facing the
twin threats of soaring oil prices and a weak European currency,
gathered in Prague for the annual meetings of the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank. The finance ministers spent the
weekend putting together joint statements intended to show their
resolve to deal with the two problems, which are threatening
current global prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   When markets opened Monday, they saw initial success on both
fronts. Oil was down on the futures market, while the euro, used by
11 European Union nations, held firm with where it finished Friday
after finance officials staged a surprise joint intervention in
currency markets to boost the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a small margin on the
Nasdaq Stock Market, while decliners took the lead on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume came to 456.24 million shares, down from 675.99
million at the same point on Friday.
</P>
<P>
