<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cracks Down on Corruption  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- A former provincial vice governor was kicked out
of China's ruling Communist Party and fired from his job with a
state-run coal and railways company for taking bribes and gifts,
state media reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Li Daqiang accepted nearly $35,000 in illegal payments from
business executives while serving with the Hubei provincial
government during the 1990s, the official Xinhua News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
   With the approval of Chinese leaders, anti-corruption
investigators expelled Li from the party and took away his vice
presidency at the state-run Shenhua Group, Xinhua said.
</P>
<P>
   Li is the latest official to fall in an ongoing crackdown on
corruption among provincial leaders. Faced with growing public
anger over graft, China has executed a former governor and other
high-ranking politicians for corruption, although many Chinese
believe well-connected officials go unpunished.
</P>
<P>
   The report did not mention any criminal charges against Li, who
reportedly accepted cash and stock in companies he helped. The
report said Li returned $12,300 to a company whose stock market
listing he assisted.
</P>
<P>
   Li ''treated his legitimate working relations with the companies
under his supervision and the lower-level government offices as an
opportunity to exchange power for financial gain,'' the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Li Daqiang slipped into the muddy pit of corruption,'' Xinhua
quoted a party report as saying. ''Faced with increasing
temptations, he relaxed his mental discipline, lost his political
alertness, lowered his behavioral standards and thought only of
gain until his intellectual line of defense collapsed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
