<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pioneering Cosmonaut Buried  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Pioneering cosmonaut Gherman Titov, the second
person to orbit the Earth, was buried Monday in Moscow's elite
Novodevichy cemetery alongside generals, writers and composers.
</P>
<P>
   Titov died Wednesday at age 65. Authorities said he suffered
accidental carbon monoxide poisoning in a sauna at his Moscow
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   His 25 hour, 18 minute flight on Aug. 6-7, 1961, followed that
of fellow Soviet Yuri Gagarin, and the suborbital missions of
Americans Alan Shepard and Gus Grissom.
</P>
<P>
   Titov marked several firsts, however. He was the first to sleep
in space, the first to spend more than a day in space, and the
first to encounter ''space sickness'' -- the nausea people sometimes
experience in zero gravity.
</P>
<P>
   He orbited 17 times, compared to three orbits for the celebrated
flight of American John Glenn almost seven months later.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet government never let Titov fly again, apparently
fearing the loss of a national hero.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's burial was attended by about 1,000 people, including
colleagues from the Soviet space program.
</P>
<P>
   ''He pulled back that heavy curtain and told us that you can
live and work there,'' said retired cosmonaut Alexei Leonov, the
first man to walk in space. Leonov also praised Titov for his
''openness of soul, and his sparkling personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Said retired cosmonaut Pavel Popovich, ''We have not just lost a
comrade in arms, but a true friend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 1326 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000925.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder, Putin Vow To Build Ties  </HEADLINE>
By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin and German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder pledged Monday to cultivate closer
ties between their nations, including an expanding economic
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder arrived in the Russian capital Monday for a few hours'
discussions with Putin, whom he last met on the sidelines of the
Millennium Summit at the United Nations earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   After their meeting in the Kremlin, Putin said the two had
discussed cooperation in high technology and the fuel crisis in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ''Russia can do much in this respect if there is good will aimed
at the long-term prospects of building our relations. ... We are
interested in that,'' Putin said. ''That will be useful for the two
countries and for Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder suggested economic ties could be improved if Germany's
HERMES credit guarantee agency could work with Russia, and if the
nation could provide new economic data to improve its credit
rating.
</P>
<P>
   The two also discussed Sunday's presidential election in
Yugoslavia, where hard-line President Slobodan Milosevic faced a
strong challenger, Vojislav Kostunica. Both Milosevic and Kostunica
were claiming victory. Schroeder said it was too early to know the
full results.
</P>
<P>
   ''We agreed ... that it looks as though Serbia and Yugoslavia
have decided in favor of a democratic change,'' Schroeder said at a
joint news conference with Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Russia backed Milosevic during NATO's bombing campaign against
Yugoslavia last year, but German officials said Russia had
indicated a desire to shift its position at the Millennium summit.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder said the talks Monday also focused on media freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ''We agreed that freedom of the press is one of the bases of
democracy. We also agreed that it's necessary to pay off debts,''
he said, according to the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring indirectly to the controversy surrounding the
private media holding company Media-Most. Last week, Media-Most
head Vladimir Gusinsky said he was pressured into signing away his
company to the Gazprom natural gas monopoly in exchange for the
state dropping fraud charges against him. It was the latest move in
what he called the government's attempt to muzzle his media's
criticism of the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   But Gazprom contends the deal was motivated by economic reasons:
Media-Most owes it hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Putin also proposed creating ''an annual Russian-German forum''
to include scientists and cultural figures, Russian news agencies
reported. Schroeder responded that the forum was a good idea, the
ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Since their first meeting, when Putin visited Berlin in June,
the two leaders have developed friendly ties, informally addressing
each other in German. Putin, a former KGB agent who served in East
Germany during the Soviet era, speaks fluent German.
</P>
<P>
   Germany has been Russia's top Western trading partner and its
leading creditor in recent years, supporting market reforms with
$67 billion in loans, grants and credit guarantees. Russia has
pushed for relief on some Soviet-era debt, but Germany has balked
at the idea.
</P>
</TEXT>
