<DOCNO> APW20000925.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Gains 13; Dow Falls 10  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned mixed Monday after faltering in a
bid to extend Friday's rebound from a market-jolting profit warning
by Intel.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the technology-led Nasdaq
composite index was up 12.67 at 3,816.43 despite an early gain of
nearly 65 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 9.62 at 10,837.75
after giving back most of an early 50-point gain, while the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index was off 2.57 at 1,446.15 and the
Russell 2000 index of smaller companies was up 1.12 at 519.94.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems was up $4.38 a share at $122.38 to lead the
Nasdaq advance, but Cisco Systems was down $1.38 at $58.94, and
Microsoft was down $2.19 at $61.06 as the Dow's weakest issue.
</P>
<P>
   Financial shares bolstered the Dow, with J.P. Morgan up $1.81 at
$169.50, Citigroup up $1.56 to $54.31 and American Express up $1.13
at $59.88.
</P>
<P>
   Among the day's big movers, Ciena rose $11.06 to $131.81 after
the maker of optical network equipment announced a major order from
Korea Telecom. Sprint PCS rose $3.88 to $31.88 after Lehman
Brothers upgraded the mobile phone company.
</P>
<P>
   The market's advance came as world finance officials, facing the
twin threats of soaring oil prices and a weak European currency,
gathered in Prague for the annual meetings of the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank. The finance ministers spent the
weekend putting together joint statements intended to show their
resolve to deal with the two problems, which are threatening
current global prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a small margin on the
Nasdaq Stock Market, while decliners took the lead on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume came to 664.98 million shares, down from 792.00
million at the same point on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
