<HEADLINE> Bradbury To Receive Writing Award  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Ray Bradbury, best known for science fiction,
will receive a lifetime achievement medal at this year's National
Book Awards ceremony for his ''tremendous impact on every genre of
writing.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Since the 1930s he has been one of America's great literary
talents,'' said Neil Baldwin, executive director of the National
Book Foundation, which gives the award in November. Bradbury joins
the likes of Toni Morrison, Eudora Welty and Studs Terkel in
receiving the honor.
</P>
<P>
   The 80-year-old author wrote ''The Martian Chronicles,''
''Farenheit 451,'' and many other books. He was first published in
1938 when his story ''Hollerbochen's Dilemma'' appeared in
''Imagination!'' magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 1535 </TRAILER>
