<HEADLINE> Stern celebrates 80th birthday at Carnegie Hall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Isaac Stern listened as some of the world's best
musicians filled Carnegie Hall with melody in celebration of his
80th birthday and 40th year as president of the famed concert
house.
</P>
<P>
   Stern led the battle to save the hall from demolition in 1960,
when he became its president. Four weeks ago, the violinist
underwent open-heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked onto the stage Sunday night, he wept as he thanked
his doctors, God and those in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ''Standing on the stage I've loved for so many years, the place
where I feel so at home, I hope it will be home to every gifted
young musician for the next 100 years,'' he said. ''I thank all
those who took part in the evening, and I thank God that I was here
to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Musicians included Yo-Yo Ma; Emanuel Ax; Yefim Bronfman; Sarah
Chang, Midori, Pinchas Zukerman, Ida Kavafian, Arnold Steinhardt,
Joel Smirnoff; Sharon Robinson; Michael Tree; Samuel Rhodes; Joel
Krosnick; Jian Wang, and Kurt Masur.
</P>
<P>
   Stern watched the gala from a box with his wife, Linda, and five
grandchildren. His two sons, Michael and David, conducted. His
daughter spoke. Stern's actual birthday was July 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
