<HEADLINE> Pataki's motor vehicles commissioner to step down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Richard Jackson Jr., the only state motor
vehicles commissioner during George Pataki's tenure as governor,
will resign at the end of October.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's resignation letter to Pataki cited his desire to spend
more time with his family and the possibility that Jackson will
resume teaching part-time, the governor's aides said Monday.
Jackson taught mathematics in Peekskill public schools from
1968-94.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 55, is a former Peekskill city councilman, deputy mayor
and, succeeding Pataki himself, mayor of Peekskill.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki praised Jackson for improving service and reducing lines
at Department of Motor Vehicle offices throughout the state.
Jackson's department has also helped the state make traffic safety
gains since 1995, according to Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson makes $120,800 a year at the DMV.
</P>
