<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fishermen worry about impending quota system  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - For the last three decades, Ernie Eldredge has
made a living pulling squid, mackerel and fluke out of Cape Cod
waters.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past few years, the 50-year-old fisherman says he's
barely broken even thanks to restrictions on what types of fish and
how much of it he can catch.
</P>
<P>
   Now Eldredge is afraid he'll go belly up unless Congress extends
a moratorium on a per-fisherman quota system he says will allow big
fishing companies to swallow the little guys.
</P>
<P>
   The moratorium - which was put in place in 1996 amid fears that
quotas would hurt the environment and small fishermen - expires
Sept. 30. And Congress has not addressed the concerns that led to
the ban.
</P>
<P>
   ''The quota system would be like telling someone who sells pants
that they can only sell five pairs of pants a week,'' Eldredge
said. ''If the quotas are based on our catch histories, the
small-boat fisheries won't be given enough to get by.''
</P>
<P>
   Eldredge and other small New England fishermen say restrictions
put in place by regional fishery management councils have already
taken their toll. They worry that quotas would leave them no choice
but to sell out to larger businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ''You'll have less people chasing more fish,'' said Ralph
Boragine, director of the Rhode Island Seafood Council. ''But that
will mean you have less people making money, buying boats, buying
food and putting money into local economies. Quotas won't just hurt
the fishermen, they'll hurt fishing towns.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers who want the moratorium lifted say quotas will promote
safety and conservation in the country's fisheries.
</P>
<P>
   ''Quotas slow down the fishery,'' said Bret Durbin, a spokesman
for Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash. ''When you have an entire season to
meet your quota, fishermen are likely to be more careful with their
own safety and take the time to make sure they cut down on
by-catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists argue the opposite, saying quotas may lead to
overfishing and ruin the small fishermen who are likely to be more
responsible than large corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The Marine Fish Conservation Network, a group of fishermen,
environmentalists and scientists, say quota allotments should be
reviewed once every five years.
</P>
<P>
   ''The decision to renew the quotas should be based on a review
of how good a steward the permit holder has been,'' said Lee
Crockett, the group's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Although Congress has had four years to figure out what to do
about quotas, only two bills this year have surfaced to address the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, introduced a bill to extend the
moratorium for three years. Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., called for
lifting the moratorium with the provision that quotas would not be
set unless three-fifths of fishermen assigned to specific fishing
regions approved their use.
</P>
<P>
   ''My bottom line is simply that I will never allow the
moratorium to expire without enacting strong protections for New
England's small boat fishermen,'' Kerry said.
</P>
<P>
   With less than a week before the moratorium expires, lawmakers
are still scrambling for a solution.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. William Delahunt, D-Mass., says the moratorium should be
extended for one year. During that time, he wants Congress to
determine a way to allow quotas while ensuring that they don't
create compensable property rights or allow large corporations to
snatch the lion's share from a fishery.
</P>
<P>
   Other New England House members support the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Connecticut has many family owned fishing businesses that
would be put in jeopardy if this moratorium is not extended,'' said
Rep. Rosa DeLauro, D-Conn. ''I supported the moratorium in 1996 and
continue to support it in the interests of ensuring the continued
viability of small fisheries and the health of our aquatic
environment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-25-00 1557 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
