<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Clearance Suspended for 32  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department has suspended the
security clearances of five employees for violations of security
policies this year, spokesman Richard Boucher said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Another 27 employees had their security clearances suspended for
other reasons in the last 18 months or two years, Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure followed announcement over the weekend that
Martin Indyk, the U.S. ambassador to Israel, was under FBI and
State Department investigation for suspected security violations.
</P>
<P>
   Indyk has lost his security clearance and no longer can
participate in Mideast diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's highly regarded for his contributions,'' Boucher said
Monday. ''Obviously, the fact that he doesn't have a security
clearance, and therefore is not able to participate in the
deliberations, makes things more difficult, because he has been an
important member of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Boucher said there was no indication of espionage and ''there
has been no indication that any intelligence information has been
compromised. This is a question of security procedures that have
not been followed.''
</P>
<P>
   Boucher provided no details of the other cases. He said he did
not know which employees had been reinstated, but said he assumed
some had been.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Sen. Rod Grams, R-Minn., dropped a hold he had placed
on seven career foreign service officers who had been nominated for
ambassadorships. They had accumulated about 100 security
violations.
</P>
<P>
   The violations reportedly included leaving safes open and
removing classified documents from embassies.
</P>
<P>
   Indyk was an important channel to Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak, who requested his return to Tel Aviv for a second tour. In
between, Indyk headed the State Department's Near East bureau.
</P>
<P>
   In both positions, and earlier as the head of the Middle East
desk at the White House, he helped shape U.S. policy on the
Arab-Israeli conflict. In a speech this month in Jerusalem he said
Israel and the Palestinians should share the Holy City.
</P>
<P>
   The first American ambassador stripped of his security
clearances, Indyk was sidelined as U.S. mediation to break a
deadlock between Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat entered
another critical stage.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Palestinian negotiators were due to resume talks
here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The deadlock centers on the future of Jerusalem and other issues
such as the disposition of hundreds of thousands of Palestinian
refugees who claim Israel expelled them.
</P>
<P>
   Indyk said in a statement this weekend: ''I regret that my
trying to do the best possible job under very difficult conditions
has led to the temporary suspension of my security clearances.
Jeopardizing the national security interests of the U.S. is
absolutely abhorrent to me, and I would never do anything to
compromise those interests.''
</P>
<P>
   He expressed gratitude that the State Department ''agreed with
my firm conviction that no classified information has been
compromised.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 1600 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000925.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State says cop killer deserves to stay in prison  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - New Jersey's Parole Board was right when it
said a convicted cop killer and former death row inmate doesn't
deserve to be released from prison, the state argued Monday before
the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas Trantino has changed into a new man since the 1963
shooting, and the board has not considered that or any other facts
besides a faulty psychological review, a defense lawyer countered.
</P>
<P>
   A lower court said Trantino should be paroled, and now the
Supreme Court must decide.
</P>
<P>
   Family of the victims said the case is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't execute him now, keep him in prison for the rest of
his life,'' Jerry Voto said, referring to the man who killed his
father. ''He's a caged animal, and he's a dog. You open up that
cage door, he'll bite somebody again.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's highest court heard arguments Monday, but offered no
decision or hint of when one would come.
</P>
<P>
   Police departments, law enforcement organizations, victim
advocates and politicians have publicly denounced the decision to
release Trantino.
</P>
<P>
   Trantino was sentenced to die for killing officers Gary Tedesco
and Peter Voto in a Lodi bar in August 1963. But when New Jersey's
death penalty was overturned in 1972, Trantino's sentence was
changed to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Sentencing guidelines in effect at the time made Trantino
eligible for parole in 1979. He has been denied parole at least
nine times during his 37 years behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   After an earlier appeal, Trantino earned another chance at
release and a hearing before the parole board.
</P>
<P>
   At a June 1999 session, the board rejected Trantino's plea for
parole. Board members relied on a number of points, including
claims by prison mental health examiners that he would likely
commit another crime.
</P>
<P>
   But Trantino argued on appeal that parole board members ignored
several key points. Trantino cited a prison record that showed no
infractions since 1970 and a report from a private doctor and other
tests that said he appeared to be a good candidate for parole.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel said in a 66-page opinion that Trantino's
latest rejection by the state parole board was ''not supported by
any credible evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   But the record before the parole board clearly shows enough
evidence to keep Trantino in prison, Deputy Attorney General Howard
McCoach told the justices.
</P>
<P>
   ''This case is about one thing. That is protecting the public's
safety,'' McCoach said.
</P>
<P>
   The board relied on a doctor's report that said Trantino suffers
from an anti-social disorder that would be exacerbated by stress if
released from prison, McCoach said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Someone who is a schemer, a plotter, a manipulator. Someone
who is deficient of a social conscience,'' McCoach said,
summarizing the medical evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Justices wanted to know what legal standards the parole board
used and what regulations it cited when Trantino's post-release
plan was called faulty.
</P>
<P>
   Court questions included what information board members had from
Trantino's various medical reports, prison records and previous
parole evaluations, and when that information was considered.
</P>
<P>
   Several questions lingered on Trantino's ability to function in
the community after almost four decades in prison. The parole board
denied release in part because Trantino had no firm plans.
</P>
<P>
   ''What happens is a person is homeless, they're denied parole?''
Justice Virginia Long asked.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Roger Lowenstein said Trantino had plans to live in
Camden, get a job, continue Alcoholics Anonymous meetings and
religious counseling with his rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   The board considered none of that in denying him parole,
Lowenstein argued. They also rejected several reports by the same
parole board psychologist who labeled Trantino anti-social, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Those earlier reports all said Trantino would likely adjust well
to parole, Lowenstein told the court.
</P>
<P>
   Trantino has admitted he was a violent, out of control young
man, but prison changed him, Lowenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ''In 1964 when he went to the death house, something happened to
Thomas Trantino, something very significant,'' Lowenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   He was repeatedly furloughed, even married during one leave.
Trantino led prison work teams and took extra classes to better
himself, the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the person the parole board doesn't want to look at,''
Lowenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General John J. Farmer Jr. said Trantino is being
treated as fairly as any other prisoner, and the fact his victims
were police officers does not weigh into the state's push to keep
him in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you look at the record before the parole board, he is being
treated like this, based on that record,'' Farmer said after the
hearing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
