<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New monument wording: less impressive, less embarrassing  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOBBS FERRY, N.Y. (AP) - The near-fantasies that were posing as
history on a George Washington monument erected in 1894 will be
covered with a bronze plaque that may seem a little less impressive
to the casual observer but will be a lot less embarrassing to those
in the know.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one will have to look at those falsehoods again,'' said
Robert Stackpole, president of the New York chapter of the Sons of
the American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   At separate meetings over the weekend, the Dobbs Ferry
Historical Society and Stackpole's group agreed to the plaque,
which is expected to cost about $2,500 plus shipping from a
Pennsylvania foundry. The Sons, who put up the original monument,
will now put up the money.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-foot-tall monument in Dobbs Ferry proclaims, erroneously,
that the village was where Washington had his headquarters during
the late stages of the Revolution; where he planned the victorious
Yorktown campaign; where French allies joined the American army;
and where arrangements were made for the British to leave the
colonies.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this monument were a true-false test, the first four
answers would be 'false,''' Stackpole said last year.
</P>
<P>
   The new plaque will say simply that the French joined the
Americans at nearby Philipsburg in August 1781, after a 19-day
march. All it claims for Dobbs Ferry is that one month earlier,
Washington had ''ordered the building of two artillery batteries
and a redoubt.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Maybe it's not much, but it's true,'' Stackpole said. One
theory about the original statements - which were known to be false
at the time they were inscribed - is that they were designed to
impart some historical cachet to Dobbs Ferry. The house that was
touted as Washington's headquarters belonged to a leader of the
emerging village and hadn't even been built at the time of the
Revolution, Stackpole said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the monument became an embarrassment, and some of
the Sons of the American Revolution wanted to sandblast the old
etching away entirely and carve the correct information onto the
original monument. Members had also hoped to get it done in time
for the 1999 bicentennial of Washington's death.
</P>
<P>
   But there was some sentiment for keeping the old wording - on
the grounds that it has become historic itself - and adding a
display to reveal the inaccuracies. Besides, sandblasting turned
out to be costlier than expected and could have been disastrous if
the old granite monument cracked or broke.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't have $25,000 to toss around,'' Stackpole said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, agreement was reached on covering, but not
destroying, the old inscription.
</P>
<P>
   Stackpole says the new plaque will be affixed to the old
monument as soon as it's ready; no date has been set for the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ''Speaking as a historian, it'll be satisfying,'' he said.
''It's been worthwhile.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-25-00 1621 </TRAILER>
