<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kostunica Lays Out Yugoslavia Plans  </HEADLINE>
By MISHA SAVIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Vojislav Kostunica, claiming victory
in presidential elections, pledged Monday to bring Yugoslavia out
of international isolation and criticized the West for policies he
said helped Slobodan Milosevic hold on to power.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Milosevic sought to head off the likelihood of defeat by
forcing a runoff, Kostunica laid out plans for once he takes
office.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must normalize relations with the world,'' Kostunica said,
praising an offer from the European Union to help develop
Yugoslavia once Milosevic is gone and democratic reforms have
begun.
</P>
<P>
   A priority, the opposition leader said, was to bring Yugoslavia
back to the ''organizations that it once helped found -- the United
Nations, the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
and ... the International Monetary Fund.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said Yugoslavia must not become ''anybody's
protectorate,'' an apparent reference to the current status of the
Serbian province of Kosovo, now jointly run by the United Nations
and the NATO-led peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   Without naming them, Kostunica also criticized former European
communist countries he said agreed to join international
organizations ''without caring much ... for (their) independence,
(their) own freedom in relations with the outside world.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an apparent reference to former Soviet bloc nations
Hungary, the Czech Republic and Poland, which joined NATO and will
be relinquishing some of their sovereign rights once they join the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
   He said people in Yugoslavia want to live in a state ''that is
not a vassal.''
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica also criticized the West, and especially the United
States, for the economic sanctions he said helped Milosevic
maintain his hold on power.
</P>
<P>
   ''Western powers, primarily the U.S. policy of sanctions against
Serbia ... enabled Milosevic's authoritarian regime to stay on. It
has thrived on isolation,'' Kostunica said.
</P>
<P>
   He specifically criticized the 1995 NATO bombing of Bosnian
Serbs and the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The West, primarily Washington, effectively created a cult of
Slobodan Milosevic,' Kostunica said. ''The international community,
the United States, saw only Slobodan Milosevic in Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he and his allies will do if Milosevic clings to
power, Kostunica said: ''Protests and demonstrations.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We will defend our victory by peaceful means ... we will
protest for as long as it takes,'' he said. ''If I had the patience
to struggle for years against communism ... I certainly won't
become impatient now.''
</P>
<P>
   Reiterating a campaign pledge, Kostunica also said he would not
extradite Milosevic or his aides to the U.N. war crimes tribunal
which indicted Milosevic on war crimes charges. He called the court
''a political institution.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not even international ... it's an American tool for
exerting pressure, and it even makes and changes its own rules
during trials, which is legally unthinkable,'' said Kostunica, a
law professor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
