<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Head Cedes No Fuel Tax Ease  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BARR
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIGHTON, England (AP) -- Treasury chief Gordon Brown, whose
budget policies have sent the Labor Party's popularity plummeting,
promised more cash to pensioners Monday but no relief to farmers
and truckers demanding lower fuel taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, in a speech to the Labor Party's annual conference, said
the nation should debate a wide range of tax and spending issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will listen and we will also make our case with the farmers
and haulers, and also with the nurses and health service workers,
the teachers and public servants, people working in manufacturing,
service and exporting sectors, and all those who depend upon our
public services,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This national debate is too important to ever be decided by
those who shout the loudest or push the hardest,'' Brown said;
protesters earlier this month dried up Britiain's gasoline
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair's government has insisted it will not
consider a reduction in fuel taxes before the annual budget is
published in March. It blames OPEC and rising world oil prices for
higher pump prices.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has the highest fuel taxes in Europe, with tax
accounting for 74 percent of the retail price.
</P>
<P>
   Although promising no relief to truckers, Brown promised more
cash to pensioners who also have been giving the government a hard
time.
</P>
<P>
   He also promised an increase in the minimum wage, but did not
give a figure.
</P>
<P>
   The fuel crisis cost Blair's government dearly, sinking its
opinion poll ratings below the opposition Conservative Party for
the first time since it took office in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup Poll published Monday in The Daily Telegraph said 37
percent of the sample believed things had gotten worse under Labor,
compared to 16 percent who felt that way a year ago; 77 percent
thought Blair handled the fuel crisis badly.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, based on 1,006 telephone interviews between Sept. 13
and Sept. 19, had a margin of error of three percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmaker Barbara Follett said she and other Labor MPs fear they
may lose their seats at the next election.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we feel very very sad not just because we are going to
lose our seats but because the country could lose a really good
government for no good reason. It is a possibility and we must be
honest about it,'' she said in an interview on British Broadcasting
Corp. radio.
</P>
<P>
   John Monks, secretary-general of the Trades Unions Congress,
said Blair's government had hurt itself through feuds and a lack of
discipline at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the hall, 1,500 people organized by the Countryside
Alliance and 150 tractors marshaled by the National Farmers Union
marched along the sea front protesting on issues ranging from the
government's wish to ban fox-hunting to fuel prices and
agricultural regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Blair must call an election before June 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
