<HEADLINE> Biomet buys Biolectron for $90 million in cash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WARSAW, Ind. (AP) - Biomet Inc. announced Monday that its EBI
subsidiary has acquired Biolectron Inc. for $90 million in cash in
a bid to expand its foothold in the market for spinal injury
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   The Warsaw-based orthopedics company said its purchase of
privately held Biolectron will allow it to tap into the Allendale,
N.J.-based company's products for spinal fusion, fracture healing
and arthroscopy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Biolectron competes effectively in high-growth market segments
where Biomet has an interest in expanding its product portfolio,''
said Dane A. Miller, Biomet's president and chief executive
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Biolectron's noninvasive spinal stimulator, SpinalPak, was
approved in September 1999 as an adjunct to spinal fusion therapy.
Biomet EBI already makes an implantable spinal fusion-stimulation
product with one of the highest success rates in the industry, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   Biomet manufactures medical devices such as orthopedic implants,
surgical instruments and operating room supplies.
</P>
