<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-CT--Sick Schools, 2nd Ld-Writethru,390  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP)- A report prepared for a legislative
committee concludes that many public schools have poor air quality
which is making children and teachers sick.
</P>
<P>
   The report, issued Monday by the Connecticut Academy of Science
and Engineering to the Legislature's Environment Committee, says
that leaky roofs and moldy carpets cause air pollution. There are
no state guidelines for keeping the air in schools clean.
</P>
<P>
   Poor air quality can lead to symptoms ranging from eye, nose and
throat irritation to headaches and lethargy that can ''degrade the
whole teaching/learning experience,'' according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   While 68 percent of schools in the state report indoor
environmental problems, the state provides no money to schools to
fix the most common culprits such as aging roofs, cracked
foundations and poorly designed ventilation systems, the report
concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Those building problems can allow for the formation of mold
spores and bacteria, sparking allergic reactions and other
symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Classroom pets and unwanted rodents in the schools also can
contribute to allergic or asthmatic reactions, said state Sen.
Eileen Daily, D-Westbrook, co-chairwoman of the Environmental
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''The entire problem has to be tackled,'' Daily said. ''The
committee felt as though we have a lot of work.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee will hold a public hearing, probably within the
next two months, Daily said, to allow members of the education and
public health committees time to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The report suggests that the General Assembly provide schools
with enough money to do the maintenance and improve air
circulation.
</P>
<P>
   While districts can get reimbursed under the school construction
program for building new schools or bringing them up to codes,
routine maintenance doesn't qualify. Other states have implemented
formal programs to enforce air quality standards in schools, the
report said, but Connecticut has no legally enforceable standards.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Werle, executive director of CASE, said the report was
intended to cause concern, not alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ''The important thing is that the Environmental Committee had a
lot of questions,'' Werle said. ''Basically, they committed they
would follow through and there would likely be legislative action
related to the subject.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
