<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge dismisses Spitzer's dredging suit against GE  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A judge Monday threw out a lawsuit the
state's attorney general filed last year seeking to get the General
Electric Co. to pay for dredging PCB-contaminated silt from an
upstate canal.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Stephen Ferradino said there are
several regulatory steps that need to take place before Attorney
General Eliot Spitzer's suit would have potential validity. As
things stand, Ferradino said the suit is ''meritless'' because it
is not ripe for judicial review.
</P>
<P>
   ''The most telling fact before the court is that no dredging has
occurred, and no permits issued,'' Ferradino wrote. ''In fact, with
the need for obtaining several permits and approvals from a variety
of agencies as a precondition for dredging, the process may never
occur.''
</P>
<P>
   The dredging of the Champlain Canal north of Albany would have
to be overseen by the state Canal Corporation with the approval of
Army Corps of Engineers, the state Department of Environmental
Conservation and the federal Environmental Protection Agency. The
Canal Corporation, which is controlled by Gov. George Pataki, has
not taken even initial steps toward dredging.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer argued that the economic viability of the Champlain
Canal is being imperiled by the presence of PCB-laden silt in at
least six choke points along the 35-mile waterway. While commercial
traffic on the waterway has become rare, the attorney general said
recreational boating is hampered by the silt.
</P>
<P>
   The waterway has not been dredged in at least 15 years, and
Spitzer said the presence of polychlorinated biphenyls in the canal
has made the process at least 10 times more expensive than if the
sediments had no PCBs in them.
</P>
<P>
   A GE spokesman praised the judge's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''As we said when the lawsuit was filed, it was meritless,''
Mark Behan said. ''It was the wrong lawsuit against the wrong party
at the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Spitzer cautioned Monday that Ferradino only called his
claim ''meritless'' because the judge determined it was not yet
ready for review by a court.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was no debate about the underlying merits of the case,''
Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the attorney general said Ferradino gave the state's
case a boost by rejecting GE's arguments that the statute of
limitations had run out for the filing of such damage claims on the
basis of pollution the company last released - legally - back in
1977.
</P>
<P>
   ''I see this as delaying our litigating this case, not as a
termination,'' Spitzer said. ''We will be back before the judge
litigating these claims.''
</P>
<P>
   The canal contamination suit is separate from the ongoing
deliberations by the federal Environmental Protection Agency on
whether to order GE to pay for the dredging of PCB ''hotspots'' in
the Hudson River north of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   GE is arguing in the EPA proceeding that the Hudson River is
getting cleaner and that dredging will expose buried PCB-laden
sediments to dispersal downstream.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Canal Corporation declined to comment on
Monday's ruling, saying the agency's lawyers had not yet seen it.
Pataki's commissioner of environmental conservation criticized the
Spitzer suit when it was filed last November, saying it would
hinder the more fundamental process of deciding whether Washington
should order the dredging of the Hudson River itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Champlain Canal is between Waterford and Whitehall, at times
running parallel to the Hudson River and at others it is part of
the river itself. Spitzer's suit was the first ever filed by the
state of New York against GE based on PCB pollution in the Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Polychlorinated biphenyls have been linked to cancer in
laboratory animals and are suspected of causing neurological
problems and other ailments in humans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-25-00 1651 </TRAILER>
