<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that were moving substantially or trading
heavily Monday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock
Market.
</P>
<P>
NYSE
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS, up $3.50 to $31.50
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers raised its investment rating on the mobile phone
company to ''buy'' and said the stock could double over the next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Kmart, down 37.5 cents at $5.38
</P>
<P>
   The retailer agreed to a new contract for 1,600 warehouse
workers that increases wages by $1.70 over three years with a
signing bonus of $2,300.
</P>
<P>
   Del Webb, up $4.94 at $27.25
</P>
<P>
   The builder of communities for older adults rejected an offer to
be acquired by rival J.F. Shea for $30 a share, or about $552
million. Del Webb, based in Phoenix, said that move would violate
antitrust laws. Shea faces potential competition in its bid from
Avatar Holdings and Pacific Partners, both of which have been
accumulating Webb shares.
</P>
<P>
NASDAQ
</P>
<P>
   Ciena, up $6.81 to $127.56
</P>
<P>
   The maker of optical network gear announced a major order from
Korea Telecom. Ciena, based in Linthicum, Md., didn't disclose the
value of the contract, but called it the largest Asian deployment
of optical transport systems for metropolitan area networking.
</P>
<P>
   Cell Pathways, down $20.69 at $9.31
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration has rejected a new drug
application for Aptosyn, an experimental treatment for precancerous
lesions in the intestines. While Cell Pathways has other drugs in
development, Aptosyn was farthest along in the process. The company
expects to receive a letter from the FDA noting the deficiencies in
the application and plans to meet with the agency to discuss the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Oratec Interventions, down $12.56 at $15.94
</P>
<P>
   The maker of medical devices that use thermal energy to treat
spine and joint disorders expects to post disappointing
third-quarter results. Oratec, based in Menlo Park., Calif., blamed
reimbursement constraints on the company's spine business and a
greater-than-expected slowdown in the summer months.
</P>
</TEXT>
