<HEADLINE> U.S. Welcomes Peru Spy's Departure  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The sudden departure of Peru's controversial
intelligence chief for Panama should facilitate the U.S. goal of
achieving democratic reform in Peru, the State Department said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimiro Montesinos, a one-time ally of President Alberto
Fujimori and head of the National Intelligence Service (SIN), was
at the center of a corruption scandal believed to have forced
Fujimori to curtail his presidency less than two months after he
was sworn in to a third term. He has promised new elections.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher noted that Panama
agreed to receive Montesinos with the strong endorsement of OAS
Secretary General Cesar Gaviria and leaders throughout the
hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do believe that this action enables the democratic process
in Peru to move forward and allows the focus to remain on ensuring
that free and fair elections and reforms to the intelligence
service, in fact, will occur,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher added that the administration does not believe that
Montesinos's presence in Panama ''excludes the possibility of
judicial proceedings being brought against him by a future Peruvian
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's re-election in May was assailed by the United States
and other hemispheric countries as flawed and prompted calls for
sweeping reforms of the intelligence service and other institutions
as a means of strengthening democratic processes. The Organization
of American States has taken the lead in encouraging reforms.
</P>
<P>
   But Elliott Abrams, a former top Latin American affairs official
at the State Department, said he believes Montesinos, with his
departure for Panama, will not be brought to justice.
</P>
<P>
   ''Montesinos is responsible for drug trafficking, arms
trafficking and human rights abuses that include torture,'' Abrams
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a mistake to let him get away scot-free. His crimes
against the people of Peru really deserve punishment if Peru is
going to move ahead to the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Montesinos' stock began to fall two weeks ago after a videotape
showed him trying to bribe an opposition congressman to join
Fujimori's alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams said that even more damaging to Montesinos were prior
allegations that he was involved in the transfer of AK-47 assault
rifles to rebels in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ''What brought him down was arms trafficking,'' Abrams said.
</P>
<P>
   Montesinos is not the first Latin American political leader to
have fled to Panama. Then-Guatemalan President Jorge Serrano tried
to establish one-man rule in 1993 and fled to Panama after the
attempt fell through. Panama has rejected Guatemalan efforts to
have Serrano extradited.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 1720 </TRAILER>
