<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Last words and lasting impressions from Sing Sing in book, exhibit  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER JORDAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUDSON, N.Y. (AP) - Shortly before he was electrocuted, Julius
Rosenberg penned a letter to his ''dearest sweethearts,'' his
children: ''Unfortunately, I may write only a few simple words; the
rest your own lives must teach you, even as mine taught me.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Christianson, a journalist and a former state criminal
justice official, also believes that words cannot teach what life's
sorrows can.
</P>
<P>
   In his book and exhibit, ''Condemned: Inside the Sing Sing Death
House,'' he offers fragments from the darkest days of more than 600
men and women silenced at Sing Sing. From 1891 to 1963, no American
prison carried out more executions.
</P>
<P>
   Final pleas for mercy, family snapshots, lists of last
possessions and last suppers, mug shots taken soon after they
learned their fate - these are the dossiers on doomed people
convicted of killing spouses or store owners or pretty little
girls.
</P>
<P>
   The fragments are intended to form an argument against the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did not want to write a polemic. I wanted to compile things
and let them speak for themselves - like the Watergate tapes,''
said Christianson. ''People should be educated as much as possible
and they have a duty to make up their own minds about it. They have
to come to terms with the realities of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Those realities include evidence of the humanity and depth of
emotion revealed by some of those seen before as cold-blooded.
</P>
<P>
   Christianson lists 18 items left behind by Ethel Rosenberg - a
book of songs, letters from her children, a small box of
handkerchiefs - and a telegram to the warden from Mary Bell
Herchenroeder of Chicago that asked, ''As an American, may I have
the privilege of pulling the switch?''
</P>
<P>
   The Rosenbergs were electrocuted for espionage in 1953, setting
off decades of debate over their guilt. Retired Soviet spy
Alexander Feklisov has said Rosernberg was a Soviet sympathizer who
handed over secrets on military electronics, but not on the atom
bomb. He said Mrs. Rosenberg played no part in spying. Feklisov's
claim is consistent with declassified U.S. intercepts of Soviet spy
communications.
</P>
<P>
   There were many more who died without much public notice,
without anyone to take their bodies home for burial.
</P>
<P>
   ''And mother since you did not come to see me. I forgive you. I
understand,'' wrote Ivory Mason, a 40-year-old janitor who was
executed in 1960 for shooting a woman. He was listed as a bigamist.
</P>
<P>
   Since May, the images have surrounded visitors to the Time and
Space Limited gallery, an old bakery warehouse turned community
arts center in Hudson, an old river city 75 miles north of
Ossining, Sing Sing's home.
</P>
<P>
   Versions of the exhibit will be displayed next in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1972, a time when Christianson believed New York would
never execute again, he has worked to publicize these photos and
words. He caught glimpses of them while working in top-level
prisons posts.
</P>
<P>
   Christianson was only able to photograph records on about 15
percent of Sing Sing's dead. These were obtained through his
request under the Freedom of Information laws. He said he's been
told the rest are lost.
</P>
<P>
   Christianson had been an investigative reporter whose stories on
police corruption for a defunct Albany paper led him to criminal
justice work. He says he resigned from state work in protest to
Gov. George Pataki's signing of the death penalty law in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   While New York has executed no one since 1963, Christianson says
his work has drawn calls from people whose lives still are marked
by the death house.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been absolutely unbelievable for me to see, 40 to 70
years after executions, the effects they still have. People have
literally been haunted by this,'' Christianson said. ''It's
something that has an impact for a very long time - like any other
murder.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit is to appear in The Puffin Room in New York City
from Oct. 20 to Dec. 31. Another version is planned for the
Kitchuan Institute in Ossining Oct. 28 to Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   www.scottchristianson.org
</P>
<P>
   ''Condemned: Inside the Sing Sing Death House'' (New York
University Press, 166 pages, $24.95)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
