<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Everglades Project in Senate Vote  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate appeared ready to give overwhelming
support Monday to what lawmakers called the largest environmental
restoration project in history -- a $7.8 billion effort expected to
take three decades to rescue the Florida Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which must still be taken up by the House,
calls for a massive federal construction project aimed at restoring
the historic water flows through the 300-mile long Everglades
ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   Despite broad bipartisan support in Congress and the support of
the White House, the measure could still face problems in the House
where it faces a battle against the clock. Supporters are hoping to
put it on a fast track in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   If passed, the Everglades rescue is likely to be the only major
environmental bill to clear the 106th Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists for years have pushed for a comprehensive,
long-term program to repair the damage caused the Everglades by
decades of flood-control efforts that disrupted the region's
natural water flow. An estimated half of the ecosystem already has
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate legislation, included in a broader water projects
bill, would authorize the first $1.4 billion installment of the
plan -- half of the money coming from the federal government and the
rest from state funds.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., called the rescue effort ''historic''
and said it will provide an environmental legacy for future
generations. Without action ''we could lose what is left'' of the
Everglades ecosystem, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Some skeptics have raised concern about the size of the federal
commitment, although the state of Florida will have to come up with
half the money. They worried that a project estimated to cost $7.8
billion today could balloon to many times that, especially since
some of the projects involve yet untested technology.
</P>
<P>
   It could become ''a giant sucking machine,'' said Sen. John
Warner, R-Va., during congressional hearings. Sen. James Inhofe,
R-Okla., worried because the funding ''is open ended.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This plan is not without risk,'' agreed Sen. Bob Smith,
R-N.H., chairman of the Environment and Natural Resources
Committee. ''... But if we do nothing. We lose the Everglades. We
need to take this risk to save this precious ecosystem.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation authorizes a broad recovery plan submitted last
year by the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers calling for a massive
''replumbing'' of the Everglades ecosystem which stretches some 300
miles from just south of Orlando, through Lake Okeechobee to
Florida Bay and the Florida Keys.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks the legislation measure gained broad support
from not only environmentalists but also agricultural interests in
Florida, including the sugar industry which often has been at odds
with environmental groups over the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also has the strong support of Florida Gov. Jeb
Bush. Florida earlier this year approved spending $2 billion over
the next 10 years, its initial contribution to the $7.8 billion
project.
</P>
<P>
   With waters seldom more than two feet deep, the Everglades were
once a vast sheet of water flowing southward, creating a home for a
huge and diverse variety of animal, plant and fish species.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1940s the Army Corps of Engineers began an ambitious
flood control project, building a vast system of dams and levees
that disrupted the natural water flows that had been the lifeline
of the Everglades ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   The flood control efforts dried up vast acres of the Everglades,
shrinking the miles of sawgrass marshes and swamlands to half of
what they had once had been. At the same time, thousands of gallons
of water that once flowed across the land, now flowed into the
ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The Corps' plan calls for getting rid of 240 miles of levees and
canals and building a network of new reservoirs, underground
aquifers and pumping stations to capture water and redistributed it
to more closely restore the natural flow of water that once marked
the ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the aim would be to continue providing South
Florida growing population with adequate water resources as well as
meeting the needs of agricultural interests, especially the
region's sugar industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is going to be a world laboratory for how we will restore
damaged environmental systems,'' said Graham. ''...It's the largest
environmental restoration project in the history of the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
