<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disputes Over Spending Bills  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Some of the disputes in the remaining spending bills
for fiscal
2001, which begins on Sunday:
<TEXT>
<P>
   --Agriculture: Lawmakers are leaning toward lifting, to some
degree, the embargo against trade in food and medicine with Cuba.
Also moving toward lifting ban against reimporting U.S.-made
pharmaceuticals, some of which sell for lower prices in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   --Commerce, Justice, State: The bill provides less than President
Clinton wants for subsidizing the hiring of local police officers
and for U.N. peacekeeping efforts.
</P>
<P>
   --District of Columbia: The measure would all but end
distribution of hypodermic needles to drug addicts by private
groups.
</P>
<P>
   --Energy and water projects: Would block the Army Corps of
Engineers from allowing more natural water flows on the Missouri
River, a fight pitting environmentalists and upstream recreation
groups against downstream farmers and barge operators.
</P>
<P>
   --Foreign aid: GOP would cut Clinton's $15 billion request by $2
billion, retain restrictions on groups that provide abortions
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   --Interior: Congress provides less than the $970 million Clinton
wants for buying land for parks, would limit administration's
ability to restrict some hard-rock mining operations and to limit
some timber harvests.
</P>
<P>
   --Labor, health and human services, education: After initial
cuts, Congress is now matching Clinton's overall $106 billion
request, but has omitted $3 billion in White House priorities.
Congressional Democrats want another $2.7 billion added on top of
Clinton's proposal. GOP wants more local say in deciding how to
spend money Clinton wants targeted at hiring teachers, repairing
schools.
</P>
<P>
   --Legislative branch: No major disagreements left, bill is
attached to separate measure financing Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
   --Transportation: Lawmakers moving toward Senate language that
would withhold some highway money for states that don't use
blood-alcohol levels of at least 0.08 percent as their standard for
determining drunk driving. An 8 percent penalty could be phased in
over four years. Also seeking compromise on limiting truck drivers'
daily hours.
</P>
<P>
   --Treasury: Roughly $200 million short of Clinton demands for the
Internal Revenue Service, counterterrorism. Bill also opens way for
$3,800 pay raise next year for members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   --Veterans, housing, environment, science: Cuts Clinton proposals
for public housing, community service, environment, NASA and
scientific research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
