<HEADLINE> Radcliffe publishing course moves to Columbia journalism school  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A prestigious six-week summer publishing program
will move from the Radcliffe Institute for Advanced Study at
Harvard to the Columbia School of Journalism, the deans of both
institutions announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Radcliffe Publishing Course, established in 1947, is taught
each summer by 100 prominent people in book, magazine and
electronic publishing. More than 4,000 students have taken the
course since its founding.
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring editors study the publishing process from the
evaluation of manuscripts to the sale and marketing of finished
products. Editors, writers, designers, advertising experts and
publicists give seminars and talk informally to students. The
intensive curriculum is designed to prepare participants to work in
publishing, and includes extensive career advising.
</P>
<P>
   ''This venerable program is a wonderful fit for our school,''
said Tom Goldstein, dean of the Columbia School of Journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ''A school of journalism offers the publishing course a
multitude of exciting opportunities. And what better place to
locate the world's best publishing course than New York?'' said
Mary Maples Dunn, acting dean of the Radcliffe program.
</P>
<P>
   The program will continue to be called the Radcliffe Publishing
Course for the next two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
