<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bills aimed at making amusement rides safer  </HEADLINE>
By SHERRY CONOHAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Despite a sharp decline in injuries on
amusement rides since regulatory laws were strengthened in 1998,
the Assembly Labor Committee on Monday began considering ways to
make them even safer.
</P>
<P>
   The committee heard testimony on a pair of bills that would
bring manufacturers under the oversight of the state Department of
Community Affairs and give a voice to operators of mobile rides.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to work to make the best laws in the nation even
better,'' said Assemblyman George F. Geist, R-Camden, chairman of
the committee and co-sponsor of the legislation aimed at improving
safety.
</P>
<P>
   One of the bills, A-2525, would give Community Affairs the power
to subpoena witnesses and documents when investigating serious
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   It would also require manufacturers to register with the state
and report any dangerous malfunctions that occurred out of state on
rides similar to those operating in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The other bill, A-2306, would replace the member of the Advisory
Board on Carnival-Amusement Ride Safety representing manufacturers
with a member for the owners and operators of mobile rides. Another
member represents owners of amusement rides at fixed locations.
</P>
<P>
   Geist said more can be done to improve safety even though
serious amusement ride injuries - defined as those involving
hospitalization or broken bones - dropped from 24 in 1997 to three
this year.
</P>
<P>
   He said his interest was spurred by serious injuries suffered on
a roller coaster in Wildwood in 1997 by then 9-year-old Patrick
McKeown, who is from Geist's hometown of Gloucester Township.
</P>
<P>
   William M. Connolly, director of the Division of Codes and
Standards for Community Affairs, said he supports the basic intent
of the legislation. However, he asked Geist for four to six weeks
to discuss it with owners, operators and manufacturers before the
committee acts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's mainly a question of the industry not fully
understanding what the legislation does and maybe we can come up
with some legislation to make it more clear and workable,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Zucker, of the New Jersey Amusement Association, said his
group has no real objections but is working on amendments with
Community Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Cooke, president of mobile carnival rides operator
Cooke's Amusements, said money from fines would be better placed in
maintenance. He called for a two-tier system, one for amusement
rides in fixed locations and the other for mobile rides.
</P>
<P>
   Geist said he expects the committee to complete work on the
bills by the end of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-25-00 1821 </TRAILER>
