<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Today' Show's Sydney Locale a Hit  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Olympics are an ongoing ratings
disappointment for NBC in prime-time but a surprise hit for the
''Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's two-hour morning news show, broadcast from Sydney,
averaged 6.7 million viewers five days last week, making it the
fourth most-watched week in the program's 49-year history. The
show's best three weeks came in early 1998 when the Monica Lewinsky
story broke.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, ''Today'' had more viewers than ABC's ''Good Morning
America'' and CBS' ''The Early Show'' combined.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really worked for us,'' said Jeff Zucker, ''Today'' show
executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to speculate why ''Today'' has succeeded with
viewers while the prime-time broadcast has not. Because of the
15-hour time difference between Sydney and the eastern United
States, NBC chose not to cover any of the Olympics events live, a
decision that has been the subject of second-guessing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today,'' however, has reported results for events that are not
shown on NBC until 12 hours later and, in some cases, has
interviewed medal winners shortly after their competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Couric and Matt Lauer broadcast ''Today'' live starting at
10 p.m. Sydney time, often with the backdrop of boisterous crowds
just leaving Olympic events.
</P>
<P>
   ''One-third of them are Australian,'' Zucker said. ''One-third
of them are Americans who are familiar with the 'Today' show. And
one-third are drunkards from pubs nearby.''
</P>
<P>
   Couric and Lauer also broadcast from Sydney during the week of
Sept. 11. That week, the ''Today'' average viewership of nearly 6
million was on par with its average audience for the rest of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   The first week in Australia, NBC pre-taped ''Today,'' showing
Sydney with a sunny backdrop. ''Good Morning America'' poked fun at
its rivals during live Olympics reports by correspondent Robin
Roberts, flashing messages like ''Really Live'' and ''It's Really
Dark Here Now!'' on the screen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
