<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lakewood rabbi gets two-month term in HUD case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - An influential Ocean County rabbi was
sentenced Monday to two months in a halfway house in a tax case in
which he forfeited a notorious Newark housing project.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Meir N. Hertz must also pay a $5,000 fine and will be on
probation for three years, under the sentence imposed by U.S.
District Judge Mary L. Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   Hertz, 51, faced up to three years in prison, but could also
have received no jail time, under federal guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Hertz, who pleaded guilty to a single criminal tax charge in
May, relinquished the Brick Towers Apartments in Newark as part of
a related civil settlement
</P>
<P>
   Under that deal, his company that controlled the apartments
agreed to pay $1 million to the U.S. Department of Housing and
Urban Development and cease operations.
</P>
<P>
   The company, BTA Properties Inc., admitted it lied to HUD, which
gave it millions of dollars in low-income housing funds, by
certifying twice in 1995 that the 298 apartments were ''decent,
safe and sanitary.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the 1,000 tenants complained for years of leaky roofs,
balky elevators and sewage backups, HUD maintained. The agency took
control of the housing project early this year.
</P>
<P>
   Hertz resigned in April as executive director of the Lakewood
Housing Authority, a move that was later revealed to be part of the
settlement. He also accepted a five-year ban on participating in
federal housing programs.
</P>
<P>
   He remains executive director of the Lakewood Township Rental
Assistance Program, Hertz lawyer Edward J. Dauber said.
</P>
<P>
   Messages left for the Lakewood mayor and deputy mayor on Monday
were not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   Hertz admitted no wrongdoing in connection with his positions at
the housing authority and the rental assistance program.
</P>
<P>
   Hertz does not preside over a congregation but is a major figure
in Lakewood's large Orthodox Jewish population.
</P>
<P>
   In pleading guilty to the tax charge, filing a false 1992
return, Hertz admitted he did not include $30,000 he received from
Brick Towers for providing management and security services through
another of his firms, Hertz Management.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his plea bargain, Hertz agreed to refile his 1992
return, as well as his 1993 return, in which he failed to report
$89,000 of income from Hertz Management. In both years, he put the
money on his children's returns, court papers showed.
</P>
<P>
   He must pay back taxes, estimated by Assistant U.S. Attorney
Perry A. Carbone at about $20,000, and penalties.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. attorney's office in Newark:
http://www.njusao.org/break.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
