<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car plunges off oceanfront parking deck, killing four  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN MATTHEWS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Four New York City nurses who died in a freak
accident in Virginia were remembered Monday as dedicated
professionals who also liked to have a good time.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were very fun loving,'' said Geraldine Natwin, who worked
with the four at St. Vincents, Manhattan for 28 years. ''They
enjoyed going on vacations together.''
</P>
<P>
   The women died Sunday when their car crashed through the
concrete-block wall of an oceanfront motel garage in Virginia Beach
and plunged 41 feet to the ground, landing upside down.
</P>
<P>
   The four were identified as Joan Ellen Walsh, 56; Mary Ann
Going, 60; Kathleen M. Mollick-Kelly, 63; and Mary Ann Dono, 60.
They had worked at St. Vincents for a combined 160 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''These women had dedicated their lives to this institution,''
said Anthony Gagliardi, the hospital's medical director. ''They
really had become a family within the St. Vincents family.''
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues said the four were known as the Golden Girls because
they spent so much time together.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were consummate professionals and they cared so much
about the children and the families,'' Natwin said. ''But despite
the seriousness of the work that we do they were able to nurture
themselves in order to nurture other people,'' Natwin said.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the women never married, and Mollick-Kelly was
divorced.
</P>
<P>
   Dono, who was the nurse manager of the hospital's Pediatrics and
Neonatal Intensive Care Unit, joined the hospital in 1961. Going,
the unit's nursing care coordinator, started in 1961; Walsh, the
unit's case manager, started in 1964; and Mollick-Kelly, the head
nurse of the pediatrics and OB/GYN outpatient clinic, joined the
hospital in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not an overstatement to note that together and
individually, they were the very essence of the mission of St.
Vincents,'' said Jane Connorton, president of the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors of two of the women were shocked to learn of the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   ''These were mature women,'' said Barbara Rogus, who lived
across the street from Walsh in the Flatbush section of Brooklyn
for more than 30 years. ''These aren't reckless individuals.
They're nurses. They're planners. As far as I'm concerned there has
to be something very very wrong that happened - maybe with the car
or with the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Joann Gilhooly, a neighbor of Dono's in Brooklyn's Bay Ridge
section, said Dono lived with her mother and was active in her
church.
</P>
<P>
   ''She gave so much of herself, and she gave not for praise, but
from her heart,'' Gilhooly said. ''She was one of the nicest people
you ever want to meet.''
</P>
<P>
   A next-door neighbor, Charles Flanagan, called Dono a hard
worker.
</P>
<P>
   ''She worked her way up through the ranks of nursing, and she
got her master's degree sometime around the age of 50,'' he said.
''She put her life into the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators on Monday found no mechanical defect in the car
and autopsies did not reveal any obvious medical explanation for
the accident, Virginia Beach police spokesman Don Rimer said.
Toxicology test results will not be available for eight to 10
weeks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rimer said there were no signs of skid marks to indicate that
the driver tried to stop. Speed and alcohol were not factors, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rimer said the women had just driven into the garage. ''They
came up the ramp and made a left turn ... and then went right
through the wall,'' which is about 3 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said they heard the car's engine revving just before
it crashed through the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Police on Monday brought in a national expert on total
destruction accidents to help examine the car, and no defects were
found. Police also were looking into whether the wall conformed to
building codes.
</P>
<P>
   St. Vincents, Manhattan, is run by St. Vincents Catholic Medical
Centers.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial at the hospital is planned sometime this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
