<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Testing lab and managers admit obstructing probe on gasoline tests  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - A testing lab and three of its managers have
admitted trying to derail a federal investigation into how doctored
data allowed up to 300 million gallons of substandard gasoline to
be sold in the New York metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   Caleb Brett U.S.A. Inc. agreed to pay a $1 million fine because
of the guilty pleas Monday and Friday from the managers.
</P>
<P>
   These guilty pleas came a year after three other managers at its
central New Jersey lab admitted they falsified data so gasoline
designed to reduce air pollution would appear to meet federal
standards.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, substandard reformulated gasoline was sold for 2
1/2 years into 1997 to motorists in Connecticut, New Jersey and New
York, according to the Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The three managers also admitted they changed data that allowed
an undetermined amount of industrial heating fuel sold to New York
utilities even though it exceeded state standards for sulfur, a
pollutant. The falsification took place from 1989-97.
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing investigation was launched when the lab operated by
Caleb Brett notified the EPA that it had discovered false data,
said Andrew Goldsmith, a Justice Department lawyer handling the
case.
</P>
<P>
   The six men who have pleaded guilty worked at a Caleb Brett lab
in Linden, an industrial city in a region dominated by giant
refineries, tank farms and ports for oceangoing vessels.
</P>
<P>
   The individual defendants each face up to several years in
prison and up to $500,000 in fines when sentenced in several months
by U.S. District Judge Harold A. Ackerman.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Houston-based company came forward, it was not
prosecuted for the falsification scheme. It was prosecuted for a
subsequent cover-up, the Justice Department said.
</P>
<P>
   After the company's disclosure, certain managers took steps to
conceal the scope of the data falsification, including Edward
Bachar, Jay Fulmer and Anthony Santiago, according to their
admissions in court.
</P>
<P>
   Bachar, 35, of Freehold, a former operations manager, pleaded
guilty to two counts, obstructing the proceedings of a federal
agency and conspiracy to make false statements.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer, 44, of Brick, the Northeast area manager of Caleb Brett,
pleaded guilty to obstructing the proceedings of a federal agency.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago, 44, of Howell, office manager at the Linden lab,
pleaded guilty to failing to tell authorities about the data
falsification.
</P>
<P>
   Bachar worked at the Linden lab from 1989-98. Fulmer and
Santiago, who worked at the lab since 1995, were fired after their
guilty pleas, company spokesman Charles Heaton said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has taken action ''to ensure this cannot happen
again,'' Heaton said.
</P>
<P>
   The managers were trying to keep the blender's business, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, three managers described how they regularly changed
figures on key readings such as oxygen content and benzene level to
satisfy one of the lab's largest customers, and sometimes destroyed
documents, so the gasoline could be sent to retailers such as Hess,
Mobil, Shell and Texaco.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme began around December 1994, when use of the
cleaner-burning reformulated gasoline became mandatory in the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   An EPA panel in July 1999 recommended that refiners reduce their
use of an additive in reformulated gasoline, MTBE, and use others
in its place, amid concern that MTBE fouls water supplies. In
March, the Clinton administration said it planned to ban MTBE. A
Senate panel took a step toward that earlier this month, but the
bill appears unlikely to get final approval before Congress
adjourns for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Pleading guilty last year were lab supervisor Ronald J. Domnik,
of Doylestown, Pa., left Caleb Brett in January 1997, and Julius
Balogh, of Somerville, and Nicholas Lehman, of Westfield, who were
fired after their guilty pleas.
</P>
<P>
   Managers named Mark Schroeder as their prime contact on behalf
of Itochu Corp., a Japanese fuel firm selling the gasoline.
Schroeder was with a Texas firm, Blending Marketing Services, a
contractor hired by Itochu.
</P>
<P>
   No listing could be found for Blending Marketing Services so
Schroeder could not be reached for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Caleb Brett is part of a British company, Intertek Testing
Services Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. attorney's office in Newark:
http://www.njusao.org/break.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
