<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain applauds Clinton and Lazio for campaign finance pact  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Sen. John McCain, a leading proponent of
national campaign finance reform, praised both Rep. Rick Lazio and
Hillary Rodham Clinton on Monday for their ''historic'' pact to ban
soft money from the U.S. Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ''I congratulate Mrs. Clinton for agreeing to this and I
congratulate my friend, Rick Lazio, for taking the lead and seeing
that this happened,'' McCain said at a press conference in lower
Manhattan's Battery Park, which featured a panoramic view of New
York Harbor, the Statue of Liberty and Ellis Island as a backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   ''This should be an example for all campaigns in America and
it's an important step in getting rid of the evil and pernicious
and corrupting influence of this so-called soft money,'' said
McCain, who has appeared in a Lazio campaign TV commercial
criticizing Clinton over soft money.
</P>
<P>
   After jousting over the issue for weeks, the campaigns reached a
deal late Saturday that prohibits the political parties endorsing
them from airing TV and radio ads boosting their candidates or
attacking their opponents. That applies to the Republican and
Conservative parties on his side and the Democratic, Liberal and
Working Families parties on her side.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement does not ban direct mail or get-out-the-vote
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money refers to unlimited funds collected by political
parties. While hard money contributions, limited to $2,000 per
donor, can be used for ads that advocate voting for or against a
candidate, soft money can only be used to advocate an issue, boost
a candidate or attack a candidate, rather than stating, ''Vote for
so-and-so.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who with Wisconsin Sen. Russ Feingold sponsored campaign
finance reform legislation in the Senate, said the example of
Clinton and Lazio should be followed by ''every federal campaign in
America ... including the presidential campaign.'' McCain and
Feingold sent a letter to all federal candidates on Sunday, urging
that they follow the example of the New York Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio turned down the chance to boast about his role in crafting
an agreement, saying, ''in the end, it was the will of the people
of the state of New York that forced this agreement. And it is an
historic agreement. ... New Yorkers don't need a law to do the
right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign has already raised millions of dollars in
soft money; Lazio's campaign does not have its own soft-money
account but has benefited from soft-money spending by outside
groups.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said despite the fact that Lazio did not have a
soft-money account, had the campaign finance talks collapsed,
''there were people who were prepared to give unlimited amounts to
Mr. Lazio. ... There was a whole lot of soft money that was going
to come into the Lazio campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in upper Manhattan, where she picked up the
endorsement of Nobel laureate and Holocaust survivor Elie Wiesel,
Clinton also referred to the pact as ''historic,'' and said she
hopes all outside parties will abide by the soft money ban.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm hopeful the agreement will hold,'' she said. ''It's an
historic agreement. I'm counting on it being enforced by everyone
who's affected by it.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to enforce the pact, the Lazio campaign released a
letter late Monday afternoon that it sent to the Conservative
Leadership Political Action Committee, asking the group to stay out
of the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign Manager Bill Dal Col said that if the group persists,
the Lazio campaign will obtain a list of the PAC's donors and
''apprise them of the fact that their hard-earned money is being
spent in a way detrimental to Congressman Lazio's campaign and
supportive of Mrs. Clinton's effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared with Wiesel to decry new textbooks being
distributed by the Palestinian Authority, some of which, she said,
equate Zionism with racism.
</P>
<P>
   ''Stop teaching hate to your children,'' Clinton said of the
Palestinan Authority. She demanded that ''all future aid to the
Palestinian Authority must be contingent on an immediate good faith
effort to change textbooks.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was also asked why the White House did not release the
dates and other information about the more than 400 guests who
either stayed at the White House or Camp David since July 1999.
Political opponents have suggested that the Clintons may have
allowed guests to stay with them in exchange for donations to her
Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''We obviously are there with our guests, but we are both very
busy people and there are last-minute changes,'' Clinton said.
''We've given information I think is more than adequate for voters
to draw any conclusion they wish to.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the state Democratic Party began to criticize Lazio
for missing votes in Washington as he campaigns for the Senate
here. ''This past week, he had a perfect voting record - Lazio
missed every single House vote,'' the party said in a press
release.
</P>
<P>
   ''They need to see the newsflash that there's a Senate race
going on in New York,'' Lazio said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-25-00 1859 </TRAILER>
