<HEADLINE> Legislators hope to end surgery that quiets barking dogs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Calling surgically altered dogs a danger to
the public, some lawmakers want to outlaw the process that silences
dogs.
</P>
<P>
   If the measure becomes law, performing the surgery would be a
crime and owners would be required to seek special permission for
the procedure. They would also be required to say if a dog has had
the surgery before getting a license.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, an Assembly committee unanimously approved bill
A-2639, and sent it to the full house for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators say dogs who have had the surgery can't warn the
public of a possible emergency. And silent dogs would give no
warning of themselves before an attack, lawmakers said.
</P>
<P>
   ''A dog that cannot bark is a potential silent killer,'' bill
sponsor Assemblyman Jerry Green, D-Union, said in a statement. ''No
neighborhood is safe if such an animal is on the loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican co-sponsor, Assemblyman Guy R. Gregg of Morris, said
the silenced dogs can give no warning before they attack.
</P>
<P>
   ''This bill provides additional safeguards against these
potentially dangerous animals which have the capacity to inflict
serious injury,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Full text of bills available at the Office of Legislative
Services Web site located at http://www.njleg.state.nj.us
</P>
</TEXT>
