<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate panel OKs bill requiring parental consent for surveys  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The Senate Education Committee on Monday
unanimously approved a bill to prevent school districts from
surveying students on sensitive questions about sex or drug use
without written permission from parents.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was triggered by the angry reaction of some parents to
a survey administered by the Ridgewood school districts to middle-
and high-school students last year with a few explicit questions
about sex, birth control, drug use and thoughts of suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many of these surveys are personal in nature and sometimes
unsuitable for minors,'' said one bill sponsor, Sen. Anthony Bucco,
R-Morris. ''Parents have a right to know what their children are
reading.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ridgewood survey, which was federally funded, drew the
attention of the Rutherford Institute of Charlottesville, Va.,
which filed a lawsuit against the district on behalf of three
parents as a test case. The Institute is seeking to outlaw such
surveys nationally.
</P>
<P>
   An institute lawyer said the issue in the lawsuit is not the
content of the survey as much as it is whether students felt
compelled by school staff to take the survey, and whether parents
were fully informed about it in advance.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate committee approved the bill in a bipartisan vote, and
it now goes to the full Senate. The bill would not prohibit such
surveys, but would allow schools to administer them only to
students whose parents had an opportunity to see the questions and
then sign a permission slip.
</P>
<P>
   Ridgewood school officials said they mailed notices home about
the survey last year and had sample copies of it available in an
office for parents to come in and read.
</P>
<P>
   Francis Edwards, a Ridgewood parent who came to the Statehouse
on Monday to testify, said most of those present at the hearing
were educational professionals opposed to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am extremely pleased that the committee moved ahead with
it,'' Edwards said. ''I was not expecting a 5-0 vote. I was
stunned. An army of detractors were there.''
--:
</P>
<P>
   Full text of bill S-1454 is available at the Office of
Legislative Services Web site located at
http://www.njleg.state.nj.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
