<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP group boosts underfunded Franks with anti-Corzine ad  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - A political group with ties to New Jersey
Republican leaders - including Gov. Christie Whitman - unveiled a
radio ad Monday that says Democratic Senate candidate Jon Corzine
''is having trouble with the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad is a breakthrough of sorts for Corzine's Republican
opponent, Rep. Bob Franks, who is struggling to raise money and has
yet to air a commercial of his own in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, by contrast, opened a million-dollar-plus per week
television blitz on Sept. 4, funded largely by his own $400 million
fortune earned during a 25-year career at Wall Street's Goldman
Sachs &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   After all but ignoring his GOP challenger, Corzine last week
introduced an ad linking Franks to former House Speaker Newt
Gingrich and to efforts to limit growth in Medicare spending.
</P>
<P>
   The new anti-Corzine ad is produced by the Washington-based
Republican Leadership Council. Whitman serves on the group's
advisory board, as does Franks.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman and Franks both have called for laws requiring
independent political groups to identify their donors, something
the RLC does not do. Corzine spokesman Tom Shea said Franks is
guilty of ''hypocrisy.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad takes Corzine to task over a dispute last week regarding
charitable donations from a foundation run by him and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Under criticism from Republicans, Corzine released details Sept.
18 on more than $10 million in checks he and the foundation wrote
to charity over the past 21 months.
</P>
<P>
   Critics seized on a handful of donations that went to groups
that are supporting Corzine's Senate run, questioning whether the
money bought Corzine political support.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest flare-up surrounded a Dec. 9, 1999, check for
$25,000 to St. Matthews AME Church in Orange. The church's pastor,
the Rev. Reginald Jackson, is director of the influential New
Jersey Black Ministers Council.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, Jackson and other key officers of the council
endorsed Corzine over his primary opponent, former Gov. Jim Florio.
At a news conference to announce the endorsement, Corzine stood
silently as a council officer answered a reporter's question by
saying Corzine had not given money to the group.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said last week that he was not a candidate for office
when he wrote the check to the ministers' group. The check was
written three months after he formally announced his candidacy, but
Corzine insists he pledged the money to the group months before
actually writing the check.
</P>
<P>
   The radio ad describes these disputes and urges listeners to
call Corzine and ''tell him trust is something his money can't
buy.'' As a so-called ''issue ad,'' the spot cannot and does not
explicitly advocate a vote against Corzine.
</P>
<P>
   The ad will run at least through Friday on radio stations in New
York City and Philadelphia during rush hour, and all day on
stations throughout New Jersey, said Mark Miller, executive
director of the Republican Leadership Council.
</P>
<P>
   Candace Straight, who is leading Franks' fund-raising efforts,
was a longtime member of the RLC's executive committee. Lewis
Eisenberg, who is now leading fund-raising efforts for the New
Jersey GOP, was its founder and chairman.
</P>
<P>
   But both of them resigned from the group in June before
beginning their new campaign roles, Miller said. He said they did
so to avoid any appearance of coordination between the RLC and the
Franks campaign, which would be illegal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
