<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Committee mulls constitutional change to allow abortion notification law </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A state Assembly committee Monday approved
changing the New Jersey Constitution to pave the way for a law
requiring minors to notify their parents before getting an abortion
or any other medical procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman last year signed a law requiring parental
notification before an abortion but the New Jersey Supreme Court -
including three justices she had appointed - struck it down last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, sponsor of the bill to change the
constitution, said such an amendment would prevent another reversal
from the state's highest court. His bill now heads to the full
Assembly, but such an amendment to the state constitution requires
voter approval, which could not occur before November 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Minors in New Jersey can now receive pregnancy care, including
abortion, and treatment for sexual diseases, drug addiction and
some mental-health problems without notifying or getting approval
from parents.
</P>
<P>
   Activists and experts presented hours of testimony to the
Assembly Judiciary Committee on Monday. But a wrenching appeal from
one Pennsylvania mother whose daughter had gotten an abortion in
Cherry Hill behind her back brought the crowded hearing room to
silence.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Carter said, ''Why would we allow a clinic, full of people
my child never met and will probably never meet again, to perform
such a serious procedure with such long-term consequences on her
without her parents' knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Carter case was part of a federal lawsuit recently settled
in which the Hatboro, Pa., school system promised to prohibit its
staff from helping students get abortions in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said she learned her daughter, then 17, had an abortion
after confronting her with hospital scrubs she found crumpled in
the girl's closet.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a horrible situation for her. We both cried,'' Carter
said. ''She is undergoing counseling. It is a one-day-at-a-time
kind of thing.
</P>
<P>
   ''She says that she thinks about this baby every day,'' the
mother added.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what she would have done had she learned about the
pregnancy beforehand, Carter said, ''I can't answer that question
because I was never given the opportunity to answer that question.
I have no idea because that was taken away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   But abortion rights activist Laurie Lowenstein told lawmakers as
grueling as Carter's experience might have been, laws cannot force
children to communicate. She said the wrong law can drive them
toward illegal abortions that are dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't make a law that forces people to trust you, no
matter how much you want it, no matter how old they are,''
Lowenstein said. ''I would rather have a living child with a secret
than a dead child.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has upheld a few parental notification
laws in other states. Pennsylvania has one. But the New Jersey
Supreme Court concluded the law was unfair here, relying on the
state's unique ''equal protection'' provision to rule that pregnant
teen-agers who want an abortion cannot be treated separately from
other teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said the phrase he wants inserted into the state
Constitution would do nothing more than solidify parental rights,
making it clear laws governing medical care for minors would have a
constitutional basis that the courts could not ignore.
</P>
<P>
   ''This just enables the Legislature to take action. Who knows if
the Legislature will act on anything,'' Collins said. ''What we are
saying is that parents' rights to the health of their minor
children is paramount in New Jersey. Simple, clear, that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Collins, who opposes abortion, said he would expect the
Legislature to promptly draft a new version of the 1999
parental-notification law if the change to the state constitution
is approved by the voters.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters assembled outside the Statehouse denounced it as a
backdoor means of restricting abortion and to get around the
state's highest court. Many of them packed the hearing room to
applaud favorable testimony, though they lost on the 5-2 vote which
followed party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblywoman Linda Greenstein, D-Middlesex, voted against the
proposal, saying Collins should have tailored the amendment
specifically to abortion if that was his interest. She feared the
current version was too broad and could open the door for
restrictions on other treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will catch all sorts of fish in this net when we put it out
there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   --:
</P>
<P>
   Full text of ACR-2 is available at the Office of Legislative
Services Web site located at http://www.njleg.state.nj.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-25-00 1949 </TRAILER>
