<HEADLINE> Lawmakers approve committee to oversee massive school building program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Once a stumbling block to making the deal,
an Assembly committee Monday agreed to the forming of a panel that
will oversee the state's massive school construction program.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers fiercely debated the need for such oversight before
passing the school construction bill in June.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey might spend up to $15 billion on school projects
across the state, spurred by a court-ordered building requirement
for the 30 poorest districts.
</P>
<P>
   About $6 billion of the funds are reserved for the special needs
schools, the remainder for richer suburban districts around the
state. The state approved $8.6 billion for the overall project, a
figure that does not include eventual interest payments and could
cost taxpayers up to $15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe any program that recommends spending $15 billion
requires legislative oversight,'' Assembly Speaker Jack Collins,
R-Salem, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly Education Committee unanimously approved the
resolution, sending it to the full house for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the committee would identify problems, develop
recommendations on school facilities and work to ensure public
participation.
</P>
</TEXT>
