<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sick-Worker Talks at House Impasse  </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE RIZZO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional negotiations on a compensation
plan for thousands of people made sick by their work at nuclear
weapons plants broke down Monday, less than a week after ill
workers came to Capitol Hill and begged lawmakers to find a
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate conferees negotiating differences on the
Defense Authorization Act reached an impasse on the compensation
issue and dropped it from their discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really pathetic what has happened here. People are going
to lose their lives. They're going to breathe their last breaths
knowing this government has not kept faith with them,'' said Rep.
Ted Strickland, D-Ohio, whose district includes the Portsmouth
Gaseous Diffusion Plant.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters hope to attach a compensation plan to another bill,
but they acknowledge that prospects are dim his late in the
congressional session.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, the Energy Department reversed 50 years of federal
policy by declaring that workers injured or killed by radiation
exposure at weapons plants should be compensated. The agency
proposed minimum lump sum payments of $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   When the Senate passed its version of the Defense Authorization
Act, it included a provision calling for $200,000 plus health
benefits for affected workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office estimated the measure would cost
taxpayers $1.7 billion over 10 years, though it has never been
established with certainty how many of the 600,000 people who
worked at the weapons plants were harmed by on-the-job exposure.
</P>
<P>
   The House, wary of passing an entitlement program whose costs
were uncertain, passed only a resolution recommending compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said he had heard reports of
the breakdown and called the development ''a great disappointment
to our Cold War heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., whose state is home to the Oak
Ridge nuclear weapons complex, expressed disgust with the House.
</P>
<P>
   ''They never put a serious offer on the table,'' he said. ''They
apparently don't agree with us that people who are sick as a result
of their service to our country deserve help.''
</P>
<P>
   The talks collapsed just days after Richardson and stricken
workers pleaded with a House panel to approve a program this year.
After the hearing, Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, chairman of the
Immigration and Claims subcommittee, said he expected that
something for the workers would be included in the defense bill.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Long, legislative director to Rep. Ed Whitfield, R-Ky.,
said the impasse came after the House negotiators refused to
include mandatory funding for a compensation program. Instead, they
offered $250 million contingent on the next Congress passing
authorizing legislation, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill numbers are HR 675, HR 3418, HR 3478, HR 3495, HR 4263,
HR 4398, HR 5189 and SB 2519
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Bill texts: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department's Radiation Exposure Compensation Program:
http://www.usdoj.gov/civil/torts/const/reca/index.htm
</P>
<P>
   Energy Department: http://www.doe.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
