<HEADLINE> Network debate canceled in U.S. Senate race  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - One of two network television showdowns in
the U.S. Senate race between Democrat Jon Corzine and Republican
Bob Franks has fallen through.
</P>
<P>
   What had been expected to be their first debate to be aired Oct.
8 on the CBS network affiliates in New York and Philadelphia could
not be arranged as hoped, and the stations were unwilling to set up
another date, according to Corzine spokesman Tom Shea.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the debate has been rescheduled on that day at cable TV
network News 12 New Jersey to be telecast live from Edison for
those subscribers who receive that channel.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves only one debate to be broadcast on TV network
affiliates. It will be taped Oct. 20 and aired Oct. 22 on NBC's
affiliates WNBC Channel 4 in New York and WCAU Channel 10 in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were more than willing to do the debate on CBS, and they
decided not to do it with us,'' said Shea. ''They are not
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks has accused Corzine of trying to avoid debates. Franks
campaign manager Charlie Smith said Monday his staff would try to
reschedule a second network debate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can only say that Jon Corzine has agreed to two network
debates. We still hope to accommodate his willingness to join us on
those,'' Smith said. ''We will certainly work to see if we can
accommodate the retired millionaire's busy schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea said he would not guarantee Corzine's participation if
Franks' staff does arrange a second network debate. ''We would have
to consider it at the time,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Other debates between Franks and Corzine have been scheduled on
New Jersey Network TV on Oct. 12 and on New Jersey 101.5 FM radio
on Oct. 16.
</P>
<P>
   During the Democratic primary, former Gov. Jim Florio attacked
Corzine repeatedly for refusing to appear in any network debates at
all.
</P>
<P>
   The two did lock horns in four debates, two before live
audiences that weren't broadcast, one on News 12 and one on NJN.
None had the audience a network broadcast would have had.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.votecorzine.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.bobfranks.com
</P>
</TEXT>
