<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opposition Party a Diverse Alliance  </HEADLINE>
By MISHA SAVIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The opposition coalition that is
claiming victory over President Slobodan Milosevic is an unlikely
alliance that includes nationalists and ethnic minorities, labor
unions and center-right technocrats.
</P>
<P>
   They came together for a common goal -- driving Milosevic from
power. If they succeed, it remains to be seen how long the
coalition can hold together in the face of monumental problems
facing this country after a decade of civil strife and economic
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The 18 members of the Democratic Opposition of Serbia include
some large, nationwide parties with branches in nearly every corner
of the country. Others are small, almost shoestring operations with
a single office and little more than a party banner, a fax machine
and lots of resolve to bring about change.
</P>
<P>
   National parties form the heart of the alliance. They include
the center-right Democratic Party, and the moderately nationalist
Democratic Party of Serbia whose leader Vojislav Kostunica
challenged Milosevic in the Sunday elections.
</P>
<P>
   Other parties include the Movement for Democratic Serbia and the
Democratic Alternative -- both headed by defectors from Milosevic,
including he former Army chief, Gen. Momcilo Perisic.
</P>
<P>
   Two parties represent the country's Muslim and ethnic Hungarians
communities. Another -- New Democracy -- attracts members from the
business community and technocrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Opposition of Serbia has also forged alliances
with independent labor unions and the popular, anti-Milosevic
student organization Otpor, or Resistance.
</P>
<P>
   The disparate nature has raised concern that the alliance may
not hold together if it does gain power. That doesn't appear to
bother Kostunica.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have pledged to remove the biggest obstacle for democracy
in Serbia -- Milosevic,'' he said. ''Only then we will really be
able to freely communicate with people without any obstacle.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, the opposition movement in Serbia, the larger of the
two Yugoslav republics, had been plagued by personal rivalries and
philosophical differences, which Milosevic exploited to cripple any
serious challenge to his rule.
</P>
<P>
   But last year's 78-day NATO bombing campaign against Yugoslavia
changed all that. With the country in ruin and NATO-led
peacekeepers in control of Kosovo province, the opposition decided
it was time to move.
</P>
<P>
   With strong encouragement from the United States and Western
European countries, opposition leaders began a series of meetings
last year which led to the alliance. When Milosevic called early
elections in July, the opposition was ready.
</P>
<P>
   The next step was to find a candidate to oppose Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best known figures, including former Belgrade mayor
Zoran Djindjic, were ruled out because long years in politics had
left them with enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic, an urbane, multilingual figure, played poorly among
rural voters because of his ''city slicker'' image.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Kostunica, a dour law professor. He was selected as the
standard-bearer because public opinion polls showed he had fewer
negatives than the others. Opposition strategists decided they
could build a favorable image for him among the public.
</P>
<P>
   A nod to their success came Monday from Vuk Draskovic, the
leader of Yugoslavia's largest opposition party -- a longtime
maverick who frustrated other anti-Milosevic forces with his
refusal to unite with them.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic, whose Serbian Renewal Movement candidate scored low
in the vote counts, admitted he had been wrong not to join in
backing Kostunica.
</P>
<P>
   ''We made mistakes for not staying allied with the Democratic
Opposition of Serbia,'' he said in the Montenegrin capital
Podgorica, offering to resign as his party's chief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 2029 </TRAILER>
