<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman stumps for Senate, VP  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW DALY
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLETOWN, Conn (AP) - Joseph Lieberman returned home Monday,
campaigning for re-election to the U.S. Senate while raising
millions of dollars for Democrats as the party's vice presidential
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The dual purposes of the two-term senator's visit were evident
throughout the day. While the media asked him about the Senate race
against Republican Philip Giordano, party insiders celebrated
Lieberman's vice presidential nomination and helped him raise an
estimated $3.3 million for the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   At an appearance in Middletown - the first of a half-dozen stops
- Lieberman vowed to stay in the Senate race despite increasing
criticism from inside and outside the party. A recent Quinnipiac
University poll found that state voters were evenly split over
Lieberman's decision to run for both offices, with 46 percent
disapproving of Lieberman's dual candidacies and 45 percent
approving.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one in four voters said they were less likely to vote for
him for Senate because of his dual candidacies.
</P>
<P>
   But his supporters said they expected to vote for him twice in
November.
</P>
<P>
   ''He should stay in both. For him to drop out at this stage, we
would have a Democratic candidate starting way behind,'' said Jack
O'Dea, who attended Monday night's $500 per-person fund-raiser in
Stamford.
</P>
<P>
   Running for two offices is legal and has been done before - by
Lyndon Johnson in 1960 and Lloyd Bentsen in 1988, Lieberman said.
And the same Quinnipiac poll showed him with an 80 percent
job-approval rating in Connecticut, Lieberman noted.
</P>
<P>
   ''I understand this is an unusual situation,'' Lieberman told
reporters. ''In a sense, I and my extended family in Connecticut -
that is, the people of Connecticut - have agreed to disagree''
about the dual candidacies.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman would not commit to a debate against Giordano, the
Waterbury mayor who has accused him of being an absentee senator
since his elevation to the national ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said he is focusing on a scheduled Oct. 5 debate
against Republican vice presidential candidate Dick Cheney and will
not decide on a Senate debate until after that event.
</P>
<P>
   ''People in the state know my record,'' he said, adding that he
hopes people in Connecticut watch the national debate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would say to Mayor Giordano that he doesn't have to have a
debate to tell the people of Connecticut what he would do if he
were their senator. That's what a campaign is all about,''
Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   That answer did not satisfy Giordano, who held a news conference
at the Capitol to denounce Lieberman for dodging him.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has time to come to Connecticut to collect money,
Giordano said, but apparently does not have time to engage in a
Senate debate.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're depriving the state of Connecticut of the essential
element of a democracy - a debate among the candidates,'' Giordano
said.
</P>
<P>
   During a jam-packed campaign day - Lieberman was making his
third visit to the state since being named to the ticket Aug. 7 -
the senator visited the Harbor Park Restaurant in Middletown to
give one of his weekly ''Joe's hero'' awards to environmentalist
Patricia Pendergrast of Chester for her work in preserving the
Connecticut River.
</P>
<P>
   He also visited a Montessori magnet school in Hartford to
announce a $1.1 million grant to put police officers in schools in
seven Connecticut communities, and a Boys &AMP; Girls Club in Shelton
to give another ''Joe's hero'' award to club founder Raymond
Lavietes.
</P>
<P>
   At a luncheon at the Hartford Club, Lieberman brought in an
estimated $1 million for Democrats. After meeting with striking
janitors in Stamford, he ended the day with fund-raisers in that
city and in Greenwich.
</P>
<P>
   University of Connecticut basketball coach Jim Calhoun, one of
nearly 100 celebrities and business leaders at the Hartford event,
said he didn't care if the subject was the Senate or the vice
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would feel that it's a visit to his home state to see the
people who really care about him,'' Calhoun said.
</P>
<P>
   AP writers Susanne Youmans and Judith Forman contributed to this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
