<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge rules that landowners can't be added to land claim lawsuit  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN KEKIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - A federal judge ruled Monday that private
landowners cannot be added to a lawsuit filed by the Oneida Indian
Nation seeking the return of ancestral lands.
</P>
<P>
   ''No private landowners will be evicted from property upon which
they are currently residing,'' U.S. District Court Judge Neal P.
McCurn wrote. Not settling the issue of adding the landowners to
the suit would ''unduly increase and further divide the entire
central New York community.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurn decided there were enough tough issues to confront
without getting bogged down in a matter which only serves to
distract everybody ''from the real task at hand - how, in the 21st
century, to reconcile the Indians' interest in their homelands with
those of current landowners who, understandably, also view the
claim area as their homeland.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on a decision reached earlier this year in a similar
case involving the Cayuga Indians, the judge also barred the
Oneidas from seeking monetary damages against the landowners. He
gave the plaintiffs 45 days to file amended complaints consistent
with his ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The Oneidas, who asked McCurn in December 1998 for permission to
expand their case, are seeking compensation for 250,000 acres in
Madison and Oneida counties they claim the state purchased
illegally in the late 18th and early 19th centuries. The Justice
Department backs the Oneidas in the case.
</P>
<P>
   McCurn said the threat of adding landowners to the lawsuit
''would only unnecessarily further prolong this litigation and
increase community tensions in the claim area.''
</P>
<P>
   The move was greeted with glee by political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a great day. We still have work to do, but this is a
great step forward,'' Sen. Charles Schumer said. ''It vindicates
what Senator (Sherwood) Boehlert and I have been saying for the
last year and a half. To put innocent landowners in a 200-year-old
claim was outrageous. I hope the Justice Department will take this
case to heart and stop being partisan and be the impartial mediator
that they should be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oneidas took McCurn's ruling in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ''This changes very little,'' Oneida Indian Nation spokesman
Mark Emery said. ''The Nation has always said it does not want
eviction or damages against private landowners. The judge's ruling
means that the litigation can finally get under way, and that the
state can no longer avoid the responsibility for its wrongdoing.
Now, the full land claim will be before the court.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurn said in the ruling that it was ''difficult, if not
impossible to see how'' leaving open the possibility that the
federal government could pursue relief against the landowners in
the future spared the public from unnecessary concern. He said it
caused the court to ''seriously question the U.S.'s intent''
regarding the landowners' status.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be unfair not to limit relief available at this stage
of the proceedings,'' McCurn wrote. ''This case is far from
ordinary. If the court takes a wait and see approach, then because
this litigation could span another decade, approximately 20,000
innocent landowners would needlessly be kept in a state of legal
limbo. The court cannot countenance such a result.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurn said the court was very much aware of the serious nature
of the land claim, but he wrote, ''It is unfathomable to this court
that the remedy for such harms, if proven, should be the eviction
of numerous private landowners more than 200 years'' later.
</P>
<P>
   The parties in the dispute tried for 16 months to sort out how
much land the Oneidas can have for their reservation in the two
counties and how much authority their sovereign government can
assert on that land. There also are legal questions about a sales
tax formula and gaming rights.
</P>
<P>
   McCurn declared an impasse in the negotiations in late June,
saying it was clear that the Oneidas and the state were unwilling
to set aside their self-interest to reach a fair settlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
