<HEADLINE> Former Sotheby's chief to pay bulk of $256 million settlement  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Art buyers and sellers will receive $512 million
from Sotheby's Holdings Inc. and Christie's International after a
deal was reached to settle charges that the auction houses fixed
fees for years.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's majority shareholder and former chairman A. Alfred
Taubman will pay $156 million of the auction house's $256 million
portion, Sotheby's announced in a news release Sunday. In exchange,
the company settled all potential claims against him.
</P>
<P>
   Taubman said he made the payment to resolve the situation and to
minimize the impact on the company ''I care about deeply.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the remaining $100 million against Sotheby's, $50 million
will be paid through transferable certificates that could be used
by sellers to reduce future commission costs. Sotheby's said it
will pay the other $50 million in cash and could take financial
action against former chief executive Diana Brooks to help cover
it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our goal over the last several months has been to put behind
us the litigation clouding Sotheby's future,'' said Michael Sovern,
the chairman of the Sotheby's board.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's and Christie's still are targets of a federal criminal
antitrust investigation. Sotheby's officials said they are
negotiating with the Justice Department and are ''optimistic that a
mutually acceptable resolution will be reached in the near
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department did not immediately return telephone
messages Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's officials would not comment on any settlement, but
said it had ''cooperated fully with the ongoing investigation of
the Department of Justice and will continue to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   The $512 million deal - split evenly by the two auction houses -
was reached Thursday by lawyers for Sotheby's, Christie's and the
120,000 buyers and sellers who filed suit in March, accusing the
companies of cooperating to fix fees as far back as 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the settlement staggered some art and antiques
dealers, who comprise a large percentage of the companies' buyers
and sellers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The amount reached is huge, perhaps significantly more than
anyone anticipated,'' Manhattan dealer Abigail Asher told The New
York Times.
</P>
<P>
   In another settlement reached Sunday to resolve a lawsuit in
which shareholders claimed the company's dealings with Christie's
depressed Sotheby's stock, Taubman agreed to pay $30 million and
Sotheby's will issue $40 million in Class A stock to plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   -----:
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's: http://www.sothebys.com
</P>
<P>
   Christie's: http://www.christies.com
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department: http://www.usdoj.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-25-00 2059 </TRAILER>
