<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Despite gag order union protests opening night at Metropolitan Opera </HEADLINE>
By LUKAS I. ALPERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Opera fans on their way to opening night at the
Metropolitan Opera to hear Mozart's masterpiece Don Giovanni were
greeted before Monday's show by the raucous cries of several
hundred union supporters protesting across the street.
</P>
<P>
   The supporters - standing behind restaurant workers who have
tried to unionize at the Metropolitan Opera - were rallying to
protest what they called union busting and pressure tactics. The
restaurant workers briefly wore gags to symbolize their plight.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a gag order issued against union organizers barring
demonstrations or distributing leaflets that defame the Met,
protesters from a variety of unions gathered to express their
discontent at the tenor of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't understand how such a renowned institution ... could
try to impact what a union can say when trying to organize these
workers to help them get better health care and a better quality of
life,'' shouted City Coucilmember Christine Quinn, to raucous
cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Met officials say the dispute does not involve them but is
between the union and Restaurant Associates.
</P>
<P>
   The Met's 95 restaurant workers are employed by Restaurant
Associates, an outside restaurant group contracted by the opera
house. Local 100 of the Hotel and Restaurant Employees
International Union has wanted to represent the workers for more
than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials say the Met's officers and board of directors
could influence the restaurant management's treatment of the
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Food service workers at Lincoln Center's two other large
auditoriums, Avery Fisher Hall and the New York State Theater, who
also work for Restaurant Associates, are unionized, union officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Several restaurant workers and union officials accused
Restaurant Associates of union busting and using pressure tactics
to make organizing more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we want is the right to organize,'' said Noemi Fulgencio,
a cashier at the Metropolitan Restaurant for nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   Fulgencio said after 80 percent of the restaurant's employees
signed a petition to organize that ''the company began waging a
campaign to break us.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They have offered people higher pay to try and make them break
ranks. They make us watch anti-union videos and have us have
meetings with management to pressure us to cease trying to
organize,' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Messages left at Lincoln Center and with Restaurant Associates
were not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said that the National Labor Relations has
charged Restaurant Associates with 25 violations of threatening and
coercing workers attempting to organize.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 31 union supporters were arrested in front of the
Metropolitan Opera during a similar opening night protest. No
arrests were made Monday night, a police spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are committed to this and no matter how many opening nights
it takes, we'll be here,'' said Henry Tamarin, president of Local
100.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
