<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inspector Accused of Border Bribes  </HEADLINE>
By BEN FOX
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- A U.S. immigration inspector was accused on
Monday of taking at least $90,000 from Mexican smugglers to allow
drugs and illegal immigrants through his inspection lane at the
U.S.-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities said Jose Antonio Olvera, 36, of Chula
Vista, received $2,000 to $4,000 for each load of drugs or
immigrants over the two-year period he was under investigation. He
was the fourth border inspector to be charged at the San Ysidro
crossing in the last 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   A federal indictment charges Olvera with bribery and conspiracy
and also names four Mexicans who allegedly paid him and did the
smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation began after a federal agent with a
drug-detecting dog stopped a pickup truck carrying 1,000 pounds of
marijuana as it approached Olvera's inspection lane. The drugs were
so poorly concealed the agent became suspicious and reported
Olvera.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious charge, bribery, carries a maximum prison
sentence of 15 years. Conspiracy to smuggle marijuana can bring up
to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is tantamount to treason when those who are entrusted to be
our first line of defense at our ports of entry violate their oath
of office by succumbing to bribery,'' U.S. Attorney Gregory Vega
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Olvera, who was arrested at his home Friday, earned between
$36,000 and $46,000 a year as an immigration inspector, according
to the INS.
</P>
<P>
   Neither he nor his lawyer could be reached for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
