<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two indicted for beating inmate at Nassau County Correction Center  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) - A correction officer was indicted Monday on
charges he assaulted an inmate at the Nassau County Correctional
Center and then filed a false report in an attempt to cover up the
beating.
</P>
<P>
   Correction Officer Alberto Roman, 44, was indicted on assault
and offering a false instrument for filing.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Selover, a Sheriff's Department corporal, was also
indicted on a charge of offering a false instrument for filing.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Denis Dillon charges that Roman, 43, and other
guards assaulted inmate Robert Semprini on Feb. 23, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The fight stemmed from an argument between Roman and Semprini
and then turned physical, according to court documents. Semprini
was kicked repeatedly by Roman and other correction officers, court
documents allege.
</P>
<P>
   The documents also allege that Roman stomped on Semprini's head,
causing a small cut.
</P>
<P>
   Roman and Selover submitted reports claiming the inmate struck
the first blow and that Roman delivered a single blow in return,
Dillon said.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, both men could face a maximum sentence of up to
four years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment comes less than a month after a report issued by
the federal government found there was a ''pattern or practice'' of
physical abuse of inmates in Nassau County jails.
</P>
<P>
   The report followed a May conviction of three correction
officers in the fatal beating of an inmate amid allegations of
widespread abuse of inmates at the hands of correction officers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
