<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman's Dual Race Has Critics  </HEADLINE>
By BRIGITTE GREENBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHELTON, Conn. (AP) -- Joseph Lieberman took a detour from the
vice presidential campaign trail Monday, returning home to campaign
for a Senate seat that he acknowledged many voters want him to give
up.
</P>
<P>
   State law allows him to compete for both offices at the same
time, but a recent poll showed Connecticut voters evenly split over
whether he should do so, with 46 percent disapproving and 45
percent approving.
</P>
<P>
   ''I understand this is an unusual situation,'' Lieberman told
reporters. ''In a sense, I and my extended family in Connecticut,
that is the people of Connecticut, have agreed to disagree.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the same poll showed Connecticut voters giving him
a lofty approval rating of 80 percent; he holds a wide lead over
his Senate challenger.
</P>
<P>
   One voter, Chuck Scarlott, 70, of Deep River, said he would cast
his ballot for Lieberman for vice president but wouldn't vote for
anyone in the Senate race ''just as a protest.''
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't ride two horses,'' Scarlott said. ''I find it hard
to understand it is anything but self-serving. ... I think he's
disserving his party and disserving his good name as an ethical
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one in four voters said they are less likely to vote for
Lieberman for Senate because of his dual candidacies, according to
the Quinnipiac University poll released last week.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's schedule Monday was a mixed bag -- some Senate
business, some Senate campaigning and some fund-raisers for the
Democratic National Committee, where his role was that of Al Gore's
running mate. Lieberman raised more than $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   During the day, he visited the Harbour Park Restaurant in
Middletown to give one of his regular ''Joe's hero'' awards to
local environmentalist Patricia Pendergrast for her work in
preserving the Connecticut River. He visited a Montessori magnet
school in Hartford to announce a $1.1 million grant to put police
officers in schools in seven Connecticut communities. In Shelton,
he visited a Boys &AMP; Girls Club to give another ''Joe's hero'' award
to club founder Raymond Lavietes.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Lieberman's vice presidential campaign staff dropped out
of sight for the day to avoid any violation of Federal Election
Commission rules, and some old faces from his Senate office
reappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman leads his Republican Senate challenger, Waterbury
Mayor Philip Giordano, by 72 percent to 19 percent, the poll said.
His job approval was a record for elected officials in the three
states where Quinnipiac polls are taken -- Connecticut, New York and
New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano has accused Lieberman of neglecting his job and being
an absentee politician, noting he missed last week's Senate
approval of permanent normal trade status for China. He also
accused Lieberman of ducking debates.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he doesn't have time for us in the state of Connecticut,
then I think he should think about resigning his seat,'' Giordano
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate debate is scheduled for Oct. 19, but Lieberman has not
committed to attending. Lieberman said Monday he was focused on
preparing for his debate Oct. 5 with his Republican rival for the
vice presidency, Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an important debate, and I obviously hope that my friends
here in Connecticut will be watching. I'm not going to make a
decision about the other debate until that's over,'' he said,
adding that state voters know his record.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said he should stay in the Senate race because there
is not enough time to hold a primary to find a replacement, and a
handful of party leaders would choose his successor if he quit.
Attorney General Dick Blumenthal, a Democrat, has been widely
mentioned as a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   If Lieberman becomes vice president, Republican Gov. John G.
Rowland would appoint a replacement. Rowland has said his short
list would include Republican Reps. Christopher Shays and Nancy
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   By law, a special election would be held in 2002 to fill the
seat, but the state Legislature could call an election sooner.
Lieberman called for a special election early next year; Rowland
has said he would veto any bill setting a special Senate election
in less than two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
