<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cheney Cites Gore Family Oil Stock  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN GULLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Ohio (AP) -- Dick Cheney said Monday that Democratic
presidential nominee Al Gore has an oil-related conflict of
interest because of a family trust that holds stock in Occidental
Petroleum Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said that last June Gore had advocated extending a
moratorium on royalties U.S. companies would have to pay to drill
for natural gas in the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the time, it was clear that perhaps the biggest beneficiary
of the proposed extension was Occidental Oil,'' the Republican vice
presidential candidate said after giving a speech at an airplane
parts plant. He said Gore should step aside from any decisions that
would affect the price of Occidental stock or else the family trust
should sell the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney was trying to revive an issue that GOP presidential
candidate George W. Bush briefly raised last May. The effort comes
as the administration's decision to tap the Strategic Petroleum
Reserve to lower fuel prices has put oil back in the news.
</P>
<P>
   The Occidental stock, valued at as much as $500,000, was among
the assets left by Gore's father, former Sen. Albert Gore, when he
died last December.
</P>
<P>
   ''According to his will, that was put into a trust fund to
benefit my mother for the remainder of her life,'' candidate Gore
said when Bush brought up the subject in May.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Doug Hattaway said Monday in response to Cheney's
criticism, ''Bush and Cheney have been carrying water for their
friends in the oil industry and they are obviously on the defensive
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that Gore has no control over investments in the trust
fund so he has no way of knowing whether it will contain the
Occidental stock when his mother dies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cheney is obviously feeling the heat,'' Hattaway said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who retired last month as the chief executive officer of
Halliburton Co., a Dallas-based oil services company, has been
criticized by Democrats for his industry connections as he has
advocated developing domestic oil reserves and building new
refineries.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Cheney have promoted these ideas for dealing with the
problem of rising gasoline prices and have criticized the Clinton
administration for blocking such measures, including drilling for
oil in Alaskan wilderness. The Democrats have consistently
portrayed Cheney and Bush, the Texas governor who's a former
oilman, as the ''Big Oil'' ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who made millions on the salary and stock he received
during his tenure at Halliburton, has said he plans to divest his
holdings in the company if elected in November.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've severed my ties with Halliburton and I'm not a public
official. He is,'' Cheney said of Gore in response to questions
about whether he also has a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ''continues to be the prospective beneficiary of the
holding of stock of Occidental Petroleum,'' said Cheney. ''I think
that does constitute a conflict of interest for him. It strikes me
that as long as that prospective benefit is there for him, as the
heir to that trust, it's inappropriate for him to be advocating a
position that is linked to Occidental's financial health.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Cheney also promoted Bush's tax-cut plans at a steel
plant and inspected the damage in Xenia, Ohio, where a tornado
struck last week. He later flew to Traverse City, Mich., where he
discussed Bush's education proposals at a PTA meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, accompanied by Gov. Bob Taft, Cheney toured several
blocks of the town, visiting with residents and relief workers.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a mark of a strong community that people stepped up as
quickly as they did,'' Cheney said.
</P>
<P>
   Taft said he had asked President Clinton to declare the area a
federal disaster site so people could get low-interest loans and
other help.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign said there were numerous instances in the
1980s when Cheney, then a congressman from Wyoming, voted against
increases in spending for the Federal Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney ''has a long and dubious record for opposing disaster
relief and funding,'' said spokeswoman Kym Spell.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney spokeswoman Juleanna Glover Weiss said Cheney supports
FEMA but explained that his votes against the agency were in
opposition to spending that was ''excessive given the fiscal
deficit of the time.'' She also said he voted against FEMA when
bills were introduced in such a way that Democrats limited debate,
and when he supported President Reagan's policies.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss added that Cheney believes the agency is doing ''important
work such as what we saw in Xenia, Ohio, and he would be happy to
support FEMA as vice president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 2210 </TRAILER>
