<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Orders Pinochet Medical Tests  </HEADLINE>
By EVA VERGARA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- A judge on Monday ordered Gen. Augusto
Pinochet to undergo medical tests to determine whether the former
dictator is mentally fit to stand trial on human rights charges
stemming from the killing of political dissidents during his
1973-1990 regime.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Juan Guzman said the 84-year-old Pinochet must be examined
by state doctors within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court last month stripped Pinochet of immunity so he
can be tried in the alleged slaying of 72 political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The episode, in which a traveling military squad killed the
detainees soon after Pinochet overthrew Marxist President Salvador
Allende, became notorious as the ''caravan of death.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for relatives of the victims were not pleased with
Guzman's ruling, saying it will inevitably postpone the first legal
questioning of Pinochet, which Guzman had scheduled for Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   The tests should be conducted ''as soon as possible'' to avoid
further delays, the plaintiffs' lawyer Hugo Gutierrez told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's lawyers did not immediately comment. However, while
arguing that his ill health prevents him from properly organizing
his defense, they insist his ailments are physical, not mental.
</P>
<P>
   ''My general is not crazy,'' one of his closest aides, retired
Gen. Guillermo Garin, said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Chile's law does not exempt ill people from legal responsibility
unless they are officially declared mad or demented.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet, on a visit to the nearby resort of Vina del Mar in
early September, told reporters his ''health is good, the spirits
are fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet suffers from diabetes, has a pacemaker and suffered
three mild strokes during his 16-month house arrest in London,
which ended last March.
</P>
<P>
   He had been arrested in London on a warrant by a Spanish judge
wanting to try him on human rights charges. He was released after
British doctors said he was mentally and physically unfit to stand
trial.
</P>
<P>
   According to an official report, 3,197 people were killed or
disappeared for political reasons during Pinochet's regime.
</P>
<P>
   After the required medical exam, Pinochet still has
opportunities to drag out the legal process. As a retired army
general, he has the right to refuse being questioned in person and
respond only in writing, which lawyers say would slow the trial
down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 2219 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000925.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germans Take Bronze in Volleyball  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Germany's Jorg Ahmann and Axel Hager
completed an unlikely run to an Olympic medal, defeating Luis Maia
and Joao Brenha of Portugal 12-9, 12-6 to win the bronze in men's
beach volleyball.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team of Dain Blanton and Eric Fonoimoana faced Brazil's
third-seeded Ze Marco de Melo and Ricardo Santos later Tuesday
(Monday night EDT) for the gold.
</P>
<P>
   A steady rain and low, gray clouds forced spectators to wear
rain coats, but the cheering remained loud and regular at sold-out
Bondi Beach stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmann and Hager, seeded 15th, relied on the 6-foot-9 Hager's
dominating net play to overpower the Portuguese, who lost the
bronze-medal match for the second straight Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The first game was a seesaw battle, with the Germans taking
charge at the end by running off three straight points for the 12-9
victory. An eight-point run in the second game put the Germans up
11-3 before Portugal mounted a mild comeback, but Hager put away
the final shot for the 12-6 victory.
</P>
<P>
   If the ninth-seeded Americans were feeling any strain over
playing the Brazilians for a gold medal, they didn't show it.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're approaching it like they're another team,'' Fonoimoana
said Monday. If anyone feels pressure, he said, it should be the
Brazilians, because of the expectations of fans in a country where
volleyball is the second most popular sport after soccer.
</P>
<P>
   It comes down to one more match to claim supremacy on the sand,
a challenge Dain and Fonoimoana seem to appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   ''You always want to beat the best and they have shown they are
the best,'' Fonoimoana said of the Brazilians, who won silver and
bronze medals in women's play and were favored to take the gold in
the men's competition.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the ninth-seeded Americans had been expected to go
home much earlier. But they got their game together at the right
time, using a high-pressure, hard-serving strategy to keep
opponents off-balance.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're peaking, playing our best volleyball right now,''
Blanton said of four straight victories in the Olympics, including
a tense 15-12 triumph Sunday over Maia and Brenha of Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   In that game, the Americans trailed 11-10 after more than an
hour of play. Then the Australian referee showed them a red card
for wasting time, giving Portugal a penalty point for a 12-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that woke us up. It fired us up,'' Blanton said. He
and Fonoimoana scored five straight points, started off by two aces
from Blanton, to advance to the gold medal showdown.
</P>
<P>
   Now come the Brazilians, who are 4-0 against Blanton and
Fonoimoana, including two victories in July tournaments. Santos is
a 6-foot-8 shot-blocker with great instincts, while De Melo uses
speed and athletic ability to dig out opposition attacks and set up
his partner for kills.
</P>
<P>
   De Melo and Santos won five tournaments this year and have
reached the final four in 27 of 39 international events. By
comparison, Blanton and Fonoimoana have reached the semifinals in
five of their 23 internationals.
</P>
<P>
   The gold medal match uses a different format than the single
15-point games in previous rounds. It has 12-point games, but a
best-of-three format. The third game, if needed, would be rally
scoring, with a point awarded each time the ball is put in play,
instead of the side-out system under which only the serving team
can score.
</P>
<P>
   ''It'll be really crucial to nail that first game right away,''
Blanton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 2239 </TRAILER>
