<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Student Loses Brandeis Suit  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN FINUCANE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- A former Brandeis University student who accused
the school of unfairly disciplining him after he was accused of
rape lost his legal battle against the university in the state's
highest court.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling released Monday, the Supreme Judicial Court said
that the standards for a fair hearing that apply in court didn't
apply in the disciplinary proceeding against David Arlen Schaer and
that colleges should be given broad discretion in disciplinary
matters.
</P>
<P>
   ''The facts alleged do not show that Schaer was denied basic
fairness,'' the court said.
</P>
<P>
   Schaer, who graduated from Brandeis in 1997, was 20 when he was
accused of raping a fellow student in her dorm room in February
1996.
</P>
<P>
   He claimed the sex was consensual, and he was never criminally
charged. But the university suspended him for four months, placed
him on probation for the rest of his time at Brandeis, and ordered
him to undergo counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Schaer sued, saying the disciplinary process was flawed and
unfair.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers said the case had implications for students' rights
on campuses nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Schaer objected to the school's consideration of a statement by
a Brandeis police officer who said the woman ''looked like a rape
victim'' and to its exclusion of one expert witness, Schaer's own
sister, who was going to testify on the difference between rape and
''regretted sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandeis defended the process and was joined by other colleges
that said they had a common interest in keeping the courts out of
internal disciplinary processes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Brandeis feels vindicated that the Supreme Judicial Court
agreed that the case had no merit,'' said Brandeis attorney Alan
Rose.
</P>
<P>
   The court accepted the principle that courts should be wary
about ''interfering with academic and disciplinary decisions made
by private colleges and universities,'' the decision said. It also
said a university wasn't required to abide by the same rules as
courts considering a criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Roderick Ireland, in a dissent opinion, wrote that
Brandeis hadn't followed its own rules in conducting the
disciplinary proceeding, such as requiring a thorough
investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
