<DOCNO> APW20000925.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 23:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jury returns $4.5 billion verdict against ex-Serbian leader for horrors </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A former Bosnian Serb leader was ordered on
Monday to pay $4.5 billion in damages for atrocities committed by
his soldiers as a jury and a judge said the United States cannot
ignore genocide a world away.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very important that the United States of America rises to
the occasion when these things happen and we just don't wait for
the United Nation's War Crimes Tribunal,'' U.S. District Judge
Peter K. Leisure said in the Manhattan courtroom. ''You have done
it by rendering a verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury awarded $617 million in compensatory damages and
another $3.9 billion in punitive damages for injuries and deaths
suffered by 39 people.
</P>
<P>
   It came just weeks after a different jury in another civil trial
returned a verdict for $745 million against former Bosnian Serb
leader Radovan Karadzic. That trial focused solely on women injured
in the war.
</P>
<P>
   Karadzic, an international fugitive, has already been indicted
by the U.N. war crimes tribunal in The Hague, Netherlands, on
charges of genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Leisure, who presided over both trials, said the trials had
''historical significance.''
</P>
<P>
   Both trials featured several witnesses who traveled from Bosnia
and appeared anonymously, describing scenes so disturbing that Bill
Walters, the foreman of Monday's jury, said he had nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was not easy to come up with compensation, but it was also
not hard,'' Walters said.
</P>
<P>
   The damages were awarded to 13 women and 10 men, none of whom
was in the courtroom when the verdict was read. Walters took the
unusual step of asking the judge if the jury could make a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''Money cannot compensate these people for what they have
undergone,'' Walters said. ''It's a rather pitiful way to go about
this procedure. They can never be compensated in any way. Their
troubles will go on for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the judge, making another unusual statement in a civil
trial, said it was vital in ''our modern world where horrors like
this occur that we don't wait for the United Nation's International
War Crime Tribunal, which might or might not be effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirza Hirkich, a plaintiff who testified during the trial, said
the verdict left her feeling ''very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel great because I felt they believe us. They believe what
we went through, all those stories,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That, she said, was worth more than any money.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't believe I'm going to see a penny,'' she said. ''It's
not money that matters much to me. It matters that we show he's
really guilty. That would mean much more. I wanted all those people
to understand how guilty were all the Serbs who did bad things.''
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuit, plaintiffs alleged gross human rights abuses,
including genocide, torture, execution, forced disappearance, war
crimes and crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   They accused Karadzic of using rape and other human rights
abuses in an ethnic cleansing campaign to drive non-Serbians from
their homes in Bosnia Herzegovina and to establish Serbian control
of the region.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict followed two weeks of testimony. A 12-year-old girl
who now lives in Chicago described how her leg was blown off by a
mortar attack in Bosnia when she was 5.
</P>
<P>
   Other victims described the nightmares and difficulty they have
living after being raped repeatedly and witnessing the murders of
loved ones. Some told stories of men being forced to have sex with
one another or others being forced to drink motor oil.
</P>
<P>
   One witness said he felt cheated when there was no bullet in the
gun chamber during a game of Russian roulette. Another testified he
could not urinate for three weeks after he was forced to urinate on
the bodies of dead associates.
</P>
<P>
   Another said he saw Serbian soldiers cut off the head of one man
and play soccer with it in front of the man's friends.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was brought under a 221-year-old U.S. law letting
foreign citizens sue foreign officials and citizens for violating
the law of nations.
</P>
<P>
   Karadzic fought the claims against him through New York lawyers
for four years before telling the judge he would not defend
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''Can you really hope to find truth or do justice or protect
rights for people in distant nations?'' he wrote. ''Do you really
believe that attaching a U.S. dollar sign to human tragedy around
the world by empty judgments in uncontested lawsuits is a step
toward peace or justice?''
</P>
<P>
   The judge ruled that Karadzic defaulted in the lawsuits, leaving
the juries only to decide what he owed the plaintiffs for
compensatory and punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge suggested after Monday's verdict that Karadzic
might appeal the issue of jurisdiction to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Walters, the jury foreman, said jurors understood that a verdict
likely would never be paid but it was important to send a message
because it was clear Karadzic was responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ''The guards did the same things all over the country so there
was no doubt in our minds that there was a master plan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   United Nations: http://www.un.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-25-00 2307 </TRAILER>
