<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rugby club faces sanctions after players' late night river swim  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) - After 30 rugby players allegedly swam in
a city river clad only in underwear, the Binghamton University team
faces discipline.
</P>
<P>
   The school is treating the incident seriously due to hazing
concerns and because only five months earlier a Binghamton
University senior drowned in another river.
</P>
<P>
   Recommendations on sanctions are to be released later this week
by the Club Sports Review Committee, said university spokeswoman
Katharine Ellis. The Office of Club Sports and the Student
Association have already frozen the club's funds and prohibited it
from using university fields.
</P>
<P>
   City police investigated the Sept. 13 swim in the Chenango
River. An officer on patrol said he saw the group swimming across
the river around 9:54 p.m. None were charged with violating a city
ordinance because of the number of people involved, said Capt.
Roger Shaller. The police report does not indicate that alcohol was
involved.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement reported by Binghamton University's student
newspaper, ''Pipe Dream,'' which first reported the story, the club
team said the late night swim was not hazing but an initiation
ceremony in which players could voluntarily choose not to
participate.
</P>
<P>
   Binghamton is 67 miles south of Syracuse.
</P>
</TEXT>
