<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama President Mulls Asylum Bid  </HEADLINE>
By KATHIA MARTINEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) -- Panamanian leaders were persuaded to
let in Peru's ousted spy chief after being told Peru's military was
on the verge of launching a coup if he was refused refuge, the
foreign minister said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   President Mireya Moscoso and her advisers granted Peru's
Vladimiro Montesinos a tourist visa Monday while they considered
his request for asylum -- opposed by many here who say their country
is treated as a dumping ground for deposed Latin American
strongmen.
</P>
<P>
   Panama has come under strong pressure from Latin American
leaders, backed by the United States, to grant asylum in order to
help Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori out of a political crisis
sparked by a bribery scandal surrounding his top aide, Montesinos.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Jose Miguel Aleman said the apparent danger in
Peru posed by Montesinos -- who had allies in top military posts --
persuaded Panama to reconsider its initial refusal Saturday to take
him in.
</P>
<P>
   ''Information we received from various presidents and foreign
ministers (from Latin America) was that if Panama didn't accede,
there would be a military coup Sunday in Peru,'' Aleman told a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have reports that Peruvian troops stationed at border posts
were moving toward Lima at dawn on Sunday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aleman said the fact that many believe Montesinos' departure was
the only way to consolidate democracy in Peru ''is an indication
that he was the de facto leader in Peru.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Within that context we are reevaluating the initial refusal to
grant him asylum,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agreed with that assessment. In Peru, retired Army
General Sinecio Jarama said Fujimori and the military solved the
problem of Montesinos' fate ''by creating the fiction of the threat
of a military coup, and this fiction was spread to the foreign
ministers.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders in Peru were demanding the arrest and
prosecution of Montesinos over the bribery scandal, but there were
fears that any move against him would bring retribution from the
spy chief's military allies.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, opposition leaders harshly criticized Fujimori for
allowing Montesinos to flee the country and dodge the scandal,
after he was shown in a videotape apparently bribing an opposition
lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to an opposition demand, Fujimori formalized in writing
Monday Montesinos' removal from his post as head of the National
Intelligence Service, or SIN. In the announcement, accepting his
''resignation,'' Fujimori praised the former spy chief for his role
in the war on drugs and the successful fight against leftist
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The Montesinos scandal prompted a surprise announcement by
Fujimori on Sept. 16 that he would hold new elections in which he
would not be a candidate. He also pledged to dismantle SIN.
Opposition leaders also have accused Montesinos of blackmail,
torture, homicide, arms trafficking and links to drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Panama's initial refusal Saturday to take him in,
Montesinos arrived in the country around dawn Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Aleman said Moscoso and her advisers decided Monday to grant him
a tourist visa for one or two months while they consider the asylum
request. Aleman gave no information on Montesinos' whereabouts, but
said the Peruvian was free to move around Panama.
</P>
<P>
   Local media said the former intelligence chief was lodged in an
apartment building in Panama City's exclusive Marbella district
along with two other people who had fled Peru with him.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president of Panama's legislature, Teresa de Arias,
said Montesinos was a danger to the country because he would become
a target for attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Panama has provided asylum for several such leaders in recent
years. They include former Ecuadorean President Abdala Bucaram,
former Haitian dictator Gen. Raul Cedras, and former Guatemalan
president Jorge Serrano Elias, who attempted to seize absolute
power in his country in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
