<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-25 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Army Deserter In Jail  </HEADLINE>
By MATT MOSSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- A man who deserted the Soviet Red Army almost a
decade ago and has been on the run ever since must stay in a
Canadian detention center until the day he is deported to Russia,
immigration officials ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Arkady Bykov was 18 when he fled the Soviet army in 1991, and
after years of stealthy border crossings and life in the shadows,
arrived in Canada, hoping for asylum. But Canadian officials are
intent on sending him home, where he could face up to 20 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Bykov's hearing Monday before an immigration panel was to
determine whether he could be trusted to obey the deportation order
and not go into hiding. Officials ruled he should stay behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   ''The immigration lady says I am bad, I am dangerous for the
street,'' Bykov said by phone after Monday's hearing. ''She doesn't
say anything about what is going to happen when I go to Russia and
get sent to Siberian jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Wanda Wahnsiedler, of the Frankfurt-based International Society
for Human Rights, says deserters face abuse and neglect in Russia,
and that Bykov should not be returned home.
</P>
<P>
   Bykov's lawyer, Nancy Doray, is preparing a last-chance
application for asylum on humanitarian grounds, which Canadian
officials say they will consider. If he can't stay, Bykov is
pleading to be sent to the United States or Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Bykov was stationed in Germany for two months in 1991, a chaotic
time for the crumbling Soviet empire. He was 18 when he deserted,
spending 10 days hiding in a German forest, eating grass and
berries, he says.
</P>
<P>
   He made his way to Montreal in 1997, hoping Canada's liberal
immigration policies would guarantee him asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian officials have not obliged. But a main stumbling block
to his deportation has been the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Russian diplomats in Montreal won't issue Bykov the necessary
travel documents, saying he never applied for Russian citizenship
after the Soviet Union collapsed and is officially stateless.
Canadian authorities insist that his papers are in order and plan
to send him home.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian officials could send Bykov home at any time, but have
scheduled his next immigration hearing for Oct. 2 -- a weekly
measure required by law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-25-00 2357 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
